June Wallace loved, loved, loved Harvey’s Bristol Cream!
But, it was Harvey’s pistol cream she loved most, and she wasn’t shy about it.

Besides being perfectly sedated on sherry nearly every day of her life, often dosing off at work at the real estate office, June was always stocking up on booze for the holidays, even when she already had six full cases at home.

With her sherry-glazed holiday recipes, she was a big hit at all the pot luck dinners, especially when the glaze was on her. That’s where Harvey Bellmonte comes in.

To be exact, it was a Tuesday night in a neighboring town of Leewood, when June arrived at Roy and Kenny’s apartment—her favorite gay friends.

There was Harvey, regional sales manager for Harvey’s Bristol Cream. 
Noticing June had only four, bottles, Harvey offered her another, and a co-dependent love affair began.

While Roy and Kenny were serving the Baked Alaska in the living room, June and Harvey were baked in the kitchen, cooking up a pie in the pantry, up against a wall of Betty Cocker cake mix, and various soup. Harvey wanted to make brownies, but June rejected his advances, so the two settled for a quickie and his famous pistol cream chaser.

After ten years of marriage, the holidays are still extra fun for June, who toggles between work, the liquor store, and dialysis. It’s always Christmas at Harvey and June’s!

While wrapping sandwiches for their congregation, Judy Robertson discovered how to lock in freshness (and other things) with new Saran Wrap. 

She’s absolutely betwixt by how well just one roll can preserve an Ark’s worth of sandwiches. But her husband Dennis has other less practical ideas. 

Later that night, Dennis asks Judy to soak him up in lamp oil, wrap him from head to toe in plastic, and beat him senseless with a stick. 

Despite the fact that Dennis is a minister, he enjoys naughty play with Judy, and the two have begun experimenting with eating bologna off one another’s butt cheeks whilst slathered with various condiments. 

Dennis now asks for a “Miracle Whip Sandwich” (as code) whenever he desires their plastic adventures. However, after each “glad wrap” session, Dennis is usually not very glad at all, and consumed with guilt —enough to visit the local “shrink.” 

When he explained to the doctor, he liked to get wrapped in plastic, the doctor, an old-school jokester replied, “well, Dennis, after careful evaluation, I can clearly see your nuts.” 

On the way home, he stopped off at Shop-Rite for four more cases. When the cashier asked why he was buying so many, he raised his voice and proclaimed, “it’s all for Jesus!”

Janice Montgomery was raised to be the most perfect wife ever, by a mother and father steeped in the teachings of the Latter Day Saints.

When Janice met Tom Wallace at the LDS Country Club event in 1973, she knew she had landed
a good old fashioned man. This is why she wanted to please him in every way before they got married.

When she saw the “book of moron” by the famous author with three first names at the local Woolworths, she purchased it and ran home to read it.

When Tom came to her home to pick Janice up, he could hear loud voices upstairs in her room as he waited downstairs. He asked for permission to see what was happening, and quickly made his way up to her bedroom.

Through the closed door, he could hear Janice screaming, “Oh, hell no. Fuck that. That’s never happening,” —Janice was having a mormontary lapse of sanity. 

Janice was obviously none too pleased with the book’s sentiments, and not nearly ready to be in a strangulationship with Tom. 

That day, Janice went from Latter Day Saint to Latter Day Ain’t, all in just a few pages.

It was just another morning-after at Claire Montblanc’s home in Litchfield.

As barrels of wangs were piled knee-high on the luxurious grand staircase, Claire was overwhelmed and needed a rest after a strenuous morning of picking up dicks. 

While a women with such an impressive pedigree would never stoop so low (unless she stooped low enough) to clean up after the guests at her annual Cock Luck dinner, Claire wasn’t afraid to get her white gloves muddy.

On the night of the dinner, some arrived with a pecker of peckers, while some less adventurous women showed up with green bean casseroles, completely missing the 
point.

Luckily, one guest arrived with 2 gallons of Crisco and enough buttputty to spackle all the asses in Litchfield County, with some lubed up enough to make limbs and furniture disappear. 

As hostess with the moistest, Claire made sure everyone had plenty of assortments, sizes, shapes and insertable lengths, proving that it only takes a woman to do a man’s job!

Benedict’s wife Sharon continued in her usual style, paying absolutely no attention whatsoever to her husband, regardless of how hard he tried. Backflips, standing on his head, popping ping-pong balls out his ass....nothing worked. 

Was it because Benedict’s pickle was lacking girth in the peanus department? Quite possibly. 

After a quick visit to the local green grocer for assorted fruits and vegetables, Benedict came back to slip in a suggestion during a round of Scotch and Ray Conniff, but Sharon had no interest in his coochcumber antics.

Sharon glanced over and thought the large vegetable was slightly more cucumbersome than she could handle, but it was that very puss pickle she’d grow to love just after he left.

Sharon visited the grocery store more often than she ever expected, bringing home a vegetable medley, week-after-week.

It’s clear she owes her love of orgasmic vegetables to none other than her dear husband, Benedict. And now that everyone knows she’s not making 40 pounds of cucumber salad, she’s known about town as Mrs. Benedict Cucumberbatch, —a perfectly fitting name!

As Delores was in danger of getting sucked up by a vacuum cleaner, and possibly run over by a toy train, this damsel in distress was about to receive the gift of gifts! 

Ken McMurray loved surprises. He saved up for three months to purchase this Hoover for his wife. A gift that she would love and cherish forever, especially when she was done vacuuming and had to bend down to retract the cable that was wrapped around the leg of a table, then wrap around it around the two spools on the back  at least 15 times, and then carry it up to the closet without breaking her spleen.

Ken blames Delores for her insistence and her subtle hints that she was due for a new one.

“Ken, our vacuum cleaner has seen better days!” She’d say at the local department store, eying the gleaming new Hoovers—the stuff of her dreams. 

Ken made believe he wasn’t listening but already had it on lay-away.
 
The women of yesteryear favored these gifts as status symbols like men viewed automobiles. 
The shiny 50s car colors, the chrome plaque, the powerful engine. 

But did anything suck more than a vacuum cleaner for a gift?
Welp! Have you met the hand mixer?

On the beach, Bobby and his “uncle” George had a wonderful afternoon of photography and 
basking in the sun with their new bathing sweaters. 

“Let’s hike those up to your nipples, Bobby,” said George, as Bobby peeled off another layer of skin, itching and scratching his pimply white ass.

Uncle George’s new Kodak “Creep-O-Matic 63” with the new quiet shutter release, was great for silently taking photos of all the boys at the beach that summer—just before his arrest.

It seems the weight of wet wool caused both Bobby and George to lose their bathing suits and come out of the water stark naked. This was not a good luck for George. But it turns out George was really Bobby’s uncle.  George was taken to the police station for exposing their bellies and charged with indecent exposure. 

Once the photos were developed, they discover photos of hot dogs trees, shrimp towers, and ground beef shaped like trains!

Yes! The young man is a young Bobby West out for a day of sun and fun with his uncle.
This is where Bobby West gets all his perverted food photos from. 

Thanks, Uncle George!

In early December, 1959, Robert and Brigitte’s dinner seemed likely to be sabotaged by New England’s inclement weather.

The newspapers reported a “blizzard” was heading to the East Coast, and Litchfield would not be spared. Even the Farmer’s Almanac made an accurate prediction. But, Brigitte’s hopes were truly dashed when seven inches turned to a foot in just two hours.

Carolyn and Brett, Suzanne and Lee, Marcus and Dave were all supposed arrive at 6pm. As Robert paced, Brigitte put the finishing touches on the massive festive spread. Dave Brubeck’s “Time Out” played softly on the Magnovox console, but Robert had to keep moving the needle back to the beginning for the most perfect entrance song. The smell of pine permeated the already fragrant air, yet no one was coming.

At 7pm sharp, the phone rang, Brigitte’s heart beat out of her chest, as if the drummer boy himself was doing paradiddles with her heart. Robert raced to the phone, preparing himself for the worst.

“Bobby, it’s Lee,” a man on the other end said, breathless. 

“If it’s bad news, I don’t wanna hear it Lee,” Robert quipped. 

“Well.....” Lee dragged on, “Carolyn and Brett’s car wouldn’t start, Marcus and Dave are with us. We all piled in the my car and we’re leaving in five minutes. We’re gonna make it. They cleared North Street, but I have bad news. We’re all staying over tonight.”

“Of course you are! Of course!,” Robert said excitedly, Brigitte’s already set up the guest rooms!”

“We’ll be there within the hour!”

It would be the most magical night Brigitte and Robert would ever have in their new home on Minerva Lane—a testament to the adventurous spirit of New Englanders.

Don loved to knit, and every one knew he was bi-stitchual. 

He wasn’t a typical “male hooker” who simply used one crochet needle. That’s because big ol’ Don needed two hands for his!

He woke up every day at 6am for a month to create a sweater for his baby daughter, but was now competing against his mother-in-law Judith, in what she liked to call the “Craft Corner Deathmatch!” 

Who would finish first? Who was worthy of his wife Janine’s affections, was it Don or her mom?

Don frantically knit morning and night, and within a week, it was finally done! Judith and Don finally met at their house for the grand reveal, with Janine as the official judge.

Judith took out a beautiful 6 x 8 foot blanket adorned with flowers and leaves. Don whipped out his penis, covered in a gorgeous woolen penis cozy. While the itching was intense, Don’s Pecker Parka matched his tie perfectly and became all the rage with his friends that year. Seems like Don won this one, hands down! 

Judith had seen enough, turned fourteen shades of red, secretly giggled, and offered to make “bonerscnitzel” for lunch, — she said it was a freudian slip, but it had them all laughing all afternoon, just the same.

Turns out, Judith wasn’t all that bad. She went on to sell her penis cozies at the Ladies Auxiliary of Litchfield, earning her nearly $50,000, and enough for a Smother-In-Law extension on Don’s house.

Don wasn’t happy with this arrangement, sat on his knitting needle “by mistake” and ended his life. 

In the end, it was all just a bit too cozy for Don!

Dad was a staunch gundamentalist.
This Christmas, in 1963, he bought automatic freedom dispensers for the entire family.

The guns were just the right caliber to get their kids ready, and fully indoctrinated into a culture of “wildlife conservation,” out back in their sprawling quarter-acre parcel in Hartsdale, NY.

Sadly, a large number of children never have the opportunity to experience hunting first-hand, and more kids than ever before were living insulated from the natural environment, as they tended to stay inside to watch Leave It To Beaver, the Andy Griffith Show, and many western themed shows on the boob tube.

One day, as little Benny was watching Gunsmoke, he decided to fire a shot at his mom, who was blocking the TV, pegging her squarely in the left ass. He then mistakenly turned the gun on his dad, and rightfully popped a cap in his right ass. Benny is doing time in the local juvenile detention center. Mom and dad walk into each other frequently. 

You see, the whole family never realized how serious it was to own a gun until, Jasper the older moron, grew up to be a conspiracy-theorist, activist, fucking moron, just like his dad, mixing the natural sport with crybully political views. 
Jasper’s currently in jail awaiting trial.

It’s clear that cute Jasper went from hunting deer and bears, to getting his asscrack spackled by a 232-pound Latino bear named “Angel,” in the state penitentiary.

If you don’t want your asscrack spackled, be civil, be responsible, and don’t be like Jasper!

Everyone suffers from a little heinous anus every once in a while, right? That’s why Dad, Jerry, and Brian will be spending the rest of the night burning leaves outside in the freezing cold.

Just like their dad, Jerry and Brian’s little white asscheeks were also on fire, stoking the fumes of death in the Foster home. With a combination of baked beans and a bacon wrapped half-pound burger, their frequently activated rectal trembles drove poor Clare to near suffocation.

Night after night, it was one airborne toxic event after another.
First, dad would start with Jimmy, the youngest tooter, as he ripped through the high notes. Brian would add in the mid-section, and the three performed much like a symphony.

It wasn’t unusual for Clare to chase the boys out when their post mastication turbulence hit its stride, but soon, even more trouble would ensue. 

New neighbors Mark and Sarah Hanrahan, were horrified and called the police complaining of gun shots. When the police arrived the officers identified the sounds as a “typical 1040, also known as double-barreled ass blasters,” and ordered the boys to go back in, assuring the Hanrahan’s it wouldn’t happen again. 

But inside, make no mistake—Clare is not only a glutton for punishment. She secretly performs her own “one cheek sneak,” and no one is the wiser!

Back in 1968, at the local Harvey’s Electronics & Stereo Shop, Peggy Martin was considered the top sales lady in hi-fidelity but somewhat of a bunny boiler. 

It was on a Friday that Jimmy Weathersfield walked into a trap. He had just inherited a small fortune from the death of his uncle Wallace and he was about to splurge on a new Macintosh tube amp and turntable. But Peggy “sonic boom boom” Martin had other plans in this sound proof showroom.

As she stalked him from behind, Peggy pre-programmed the system to quickly play her favorite new album by The Shaggs, in an attempt to earjack Jimmy and seduce him. But Jimmy fell to the ground covering his ears at what he later described as “the sound a full bag of assholes makes when being poked by a nightstick.”

While Jimmy twiddled the knobs on the receiver, Peggy quickly grabbed Jimmy’s ass.
It wasn’t every day that she’d have such a tall and handsome man in her listening room. It was usually nerdy, electronics audiophiles, but this time, it was the man of her dreams and her diamond in the muff. 

As conservative as he was, Jimmy seemed to love Peggy’s freaky style, her stalker face, her bizarre taste in music, and eventually, they got married. 

At this time, for anyone still wondering what that bag of assholes actually sounds like, check out “My Pal Foot Foot” on YouTube.

We’re finally home. After three days of missing our little kitty Nemo, and traveling five hours there and five hours back, we’re back in New England and we’re enjoying ourselves today. We’re going to relax have a quiet dinner and then we’ll open up our presents to each other—my husband and I . Finally. 
.
.
.
.

Tonight for dinner, the Dillworths are featuring Prawn Stuffed Apples.

In a horrifying attempt that would have most guests running for their lives, Mary and Jeff Dillworth took out their favorite recipe, given to Mary by her aunt Gladys— a woman who thought she was the Julia Child of Park Slope.

It featured boiled prawns clutching stuffed olives while perched on red apples, as if hugging a toilet and vomiting a white and creamy unidentifiable substance.

When Mary and Jeff’s guests, Linda and Tom arrived, they instantly smelled death in the air, and somehow sensed this supper could be their last. 
Mary was actually quite fond of Linda and Tom, and wanted to make something extra special for her birthday. It was a time when lawless recipe sharing was allowed to pollute Good Housekeeping Magazine, and subsequently, the homes of millions of unsuspecting Americans. 
Linda and Tom did make it out alive after a few gags and heaves. The next day Linda made the rounds and warned others that Mary was in a bizarre cooking cult, and for months friends and neighbors stayed away.

What’s not pictured? Dessert. Rumour has it, it was octopus gelato!

Yes, it’s too bad you have to call it “meat loaf’ because “shit loaf” is more appropriate. 

Carol’s meat loaf was normally a slam dunk, but this time it was nothing short of a toilet dunk after a 12-course meal at Hardee’s. 

Packed with indigestible goodness, Carol pulled together this loaf in a pinch, and then trimmed said loaf in canned mushrooms and pearl onions. 

The unidentifiable cream center was supposedly created by mincing shiitake mushrooms with yogurt for an unmistakable takeshitty flavor. 

When Carol’s youngest son asked “what is this shit?,” she answered.
“Taste it and find out?” 

“Mom, I think you just made a deposit at the international bank o’ crap!”

Carol’s shitloaf lived in infamy for days afterwards, like the loaf that kept on loafing around, never to be forgotten. 

Recipe available at Shitty Housekeeping magazine. 
.
.
.
.

James was truly impressed with Mary’s curtains and immediately assessed they were a poly/cotton blend. Conversely, Mary was impressed with James design skills and immediately assessed she didn’t stand a chance getting him in bed.

It was a fact. James had a certain flair for textiles, having studied them at the university, while majoring in fashion. When he met Mary at the university’s cafeteria, he knew he’d met a friend for life. But Mary just couldn’t shush her bush, when it came to wanting James.

As flamgayant as he was, he was also the captain of the football team, The Trojans and played sports his whole life. The boys on the team still teased him about his puce dorm room color, and James made sure to correct anyone who called it pink! 

So what was poor Mary to do? She invited him for coffee and he went straight for Grandma’s drapes. He considered asking Mary for the remnant material so he could make a dress for her. It was then she knew he was a full on smuggler of swollen goods. 

From that point on, Mary invited James over for interior decorating advice, and the two had an understanding. She’d tell everyone they were ‘together,” and the boys on the team would leave him alone. 

She secretly hoped he’d fall in love with her, but in the end, James was gayer than a clutch purse on Tony night.

Just after Carol clubbed her dapper boyfriend Dan to death in the backyard, she took off to her mother’s in North Blackheath with his wallet and new croquet set.

Carol Brighton had a criminal record that stretched from London proper to Liverpool and beyond. Her first crime in 1964 was on Penny Lane, where she assaulted the town barber Kenny Stone with a pair of thinning scissors. 

Her second crime was just north of Birmingham in the town of Tamworth. Carol accosted an old man with a golf club, stole his groceries and called him a twisted old fruit—fleeing the scene with a bag of bananas.

When the local bobbies heard of Dan’s death in Blackheath, they quickly tracked down Carol at the Blackheath Croquet Championship Tournament. They descended on the grassy field from helicopters, where Carol was wacking balls, and Carol was arrested.

Carol had always been batfuck crazy, but it was Dan’s fruity sweater, shamelessly wrapped around his neck, that sent her into a tailspin.

Oh, Jeanette. She never had her gaydar fully re-tuned after her two other cancelled engagements. 
In this installment of As The Whirl Turns, a triple axle was not their undoing. 
.
.
.
#melodrama #soapoperas #comedyreel #parody #midcenturylife

Oh, it was much much more than just a movie! 

When Jack, Sharon, Mark and Melissa fly Pan Am, they get to experience a darkened cabin with “Theatre-in-the-Air” and 10-shows in one. 

Tonight, because of a glitch in the programming system, the entire flight was treated to dark and sweaty porn flicks. 

When the stewardess mistakenly played “Titty Titty Bang Bang,” starring extra-large Nigerian porn star “Dark Van Dick,” the passengers could barely contain their horror and hysterical laughter. 

Melissa spit her peanuts out, clear across the airplane aisle, while Mark pointed out that Dark Van Dick’s penis was indeed the size of a van. 

Even after the first error, another disaster followed — “I Cream on Jeannie” suddenly interrupted dinner, and sent the flight attendants in a panic gathering all the children and old people to the front of the cabin, while Jeannie magically disappeared from the screen in a sea of white. It was a veritable adventure even before the plane landed in Hawaii. 

At the gate, the flight attendants led the passengers off the plane with a constant hum of “We’re so very sorry. Thank you for flying Pan Am!”

It was a flight like no other in aviation history. Aloha!

It was a stupendous win for Glenville High against their rival football team, the Central High Tigers.

The team rode in coach Walker’s blue Oldsmobile as they paraded around the Glenville green, in the center of their small town.

Friends and strangers waved as the boys headed excitedly to Pat’s Luncheonette for fries and chocolate shakes. The cheerleaders and nearly every mom, dad, sister and brother in town followed in buses decorated with streamers, as they waved banners and celebrating a victorious 7-0 win. 

It was a feeling that put each of them, no matter their role, on top of the world for that short ride from the sports field to the town green. They felt famous, invincible, immortal for a short time. 

But a bittersweet feeling would accompany those delicious egg creams and gravy covered fries at Pat’s.

This would be the last game of the season, and in a few short months, many of the seniors would graduate and be off to college the following September. 

It was the final chance for Tommy Browne to ask Nadia Lapinski out to the Fall Mixer. It was the final chance to say all the things they’d meant to say all through grade school and high school. A time for second and last chances.

This was the final parade, the last ride in Coach’s Super 88, the last plate of fries at Pat’s, huddled at the counter as a team.

It was all there—an unspoken sadness among the clanking dishes and jubilant humanity in the luncheonette that afternoon. 

There was a longing for a time still in their grasp—missing a song playing on the jukebox that hadn’t even ended yet. They knew the passage of time would change them forever. The bonds they forged, for all those years, fractured by distance, jobs, families and eventually war.

It was 1961 in Glenville, USA. A time, a place, no one will likely ever forget. 
.
.
.
.

The Harlem-based group “This Dick,” belongs in the where-are-they-now-files, yet, leave it up to me to dig them out.

When Dwayne, Jermaine, and Rickey formed “This Dick,” previously “Deez Nuts,” in Harlem 1967, it was clear their manager, and seamstress Shirley Jackson had a clear-cut vision, and a fast track to inevitable disaster. But, it wasn’t just their denim explosion that caused their split.

In the mid 70s, their music reviews were scathing and somewhat racist.
Rolling Stone wrote, “a cross between Stevie Wonder and an electronics store robbery,” while Jet Magazine quipped, “Earth, Wind and Fire just changed their name to ‘Scorched Earth, Ass-wind, and FireBomb.”

But, none was more heartless and insulting than AfroJam Magazine’s review; “...for an all black band, they’ve got the rhythm of a three-legged coffee table tumbling down six flights of stairs in a Harlem project.” 

The whole mess finally fell apart during this exact photoshoot. Rickey(right) was down to his last good nerve. Even though the photographer asked the guys to make believe a hot mamma was passing by, Rickey, clearly not the cooperative dude in the band, said “bitch, I will cut you. Rickey don’t play make-believe. I keeps shit real.” 

Rickey forgot the photographer was Jermaine’s cousin, and this pushed Jermaine to his own realness limit, wrestling Rickey to the ground, ending in a blood-soaked tangle of blue jeans and flaired collars. This was the fight that permanently ended This Dick. 

Jermaine’s revenge was equally cunning, getting his solo project “Asstap” in the smash movie hit “Shaft.”

Customer support at Norelco wasn’t always so reliable, but Janine Lebuthier had all the time to wait for a representative.

With the advent of hair drying technology hitting its stride in 1965, with variable temperature control, it wasn’t uncommon for women in America to call customer support to ask what settings were best for optimum curling.

For Janine, her trouble began when Sarah Perry, lead drierologist at Norelco, answered the phone, bored to tears and ready to unload.
She was eager to tell her fairy tale divorce story to Janine—a sort of “capptive audience,” if you will.

First, she started about the restraining order, and the start of her conscious uncoupling, all this while Janine’s hair tightened and tightened around each spool. 
She continued about how her deadbeat husband led her to dollar store cookies, and bagged cereals on the bottom shelf at Shop-Rite. It was a horror.

Janine listened, but in her normal apathetic style, offered nothing but sighs and limpathy. It was when Sarah started crying that she realized she was mourning at the wrong corpse. Janine was done with this conversation and wasn’t getting the help she needed.

“Sorry m’aam, but I just called to ask how long to stay under the dryer when in the middle position!” 

Sarah had her finger in the middle position properly erected and hung up in disgust.
She threw up her arms and asked, “where can a women have an honest-to-goodness bitching session around here!”

The office was vacant. All of Sarah’s phone support co-workers had quit in frustration with Sarah, to work at the new insurance company. 

They now call homes asking about your car’s extended warranty. 
Sarah works as a divorce counselor at the state’s social services department. 

Janine never dares to call customer support when buying new appliances—she just reads the manual!

Who’s hiding under the comforter???

Betsy Walker had no idea who to vote for—the tax dodger, the thief, or the liar.
They were all corruptocrats in her eyes.

Standing next to her left with old boots and high-waters, was a liberal who smelled like skunk weed and tofu. And, to her right, an uptight conservative wearing rubber goloshes and a Mutual of Omaha umbrella he got for free.

She stood and mulled over what she had seen on the TV debates and ads, and couldn’t remember any of their names or issues.
But, she remembered the baby kisser and thought, not him!
She remembered the sweating face—not him!
She remembered “that was not intended to be a factual statement!”—Not him!
So who was left?

With her serious case of electile dysfunction, she shifted and shuffled, and finally, saw a name she remembered!
George Santos from the Pretendatarian Party.

“Ahhh finally someone I know. He’s the Queen’s son, and the man that saved 300 children in a burning school!”

Yes, Betsy. Exactly!

At last she felt satisfied, complete, and laughed all the way home on her way to enjoy her bland cereal. 

Betsy was a bonafide LOLbertarian.
If you don’t know who to vote for, just laugh your way through it and save the crying for later!

Cindy’s house hunt has been a terribly daunting task. 
It seems as if no kitchen comes close to hers back home—That is until house number 6. 

Cindy is looking at the swing stove and already getting moist with ideas for various creams and compotes. Delores, blushing with awkwardness about the cooktop, explains “well, Cindy, the owner is well—a modernist.”

more than Marla ever did. Her mouth was never dry, and her love for ballslaw was insatiable.

The greatest hits album by “Gay But Not Happy” finally hits select stores tomorrow and will be available only at Caldor and Sears.

“My Mom Never Liked You”
“Cocktails At 10am”
“We Need More Lesbian Friends”

“Why Do We Have Doilies?”
“Kill Me If I Ever Get Varicose Veins ”
“I Hate Myself for Loving Chenille” 
“My Fag Hag Left Me for Another Gay”
and the hit, “Why Do We Go To Baseball Games, Again?” 

The collection of fine unheard music is the brainchild of Bruce Elizabeth Swirly and his longtime business partner James Susan LaChance, who both hail from Fair Hope, Alabama.

Back in the 50s, as children growing up in a conservative small town, both men were teased for their good taste in fine linens and collectible toast holders. At the age of 16, Bruce met James at a local church spaghetti dinner, and the two formed “Chantilly Records,” in their grandmother’s basement.

Bruce played the clarinet and James sang in the church choir, amassing followers and fans who followed them from luncheons to brunches all up and down the south, calling their music, “self-loathing, self-deprecating, depressing and soul-crushing pieces of shit.” 

Finally, at the age of 37, after recording over 6,000 songs, the two separated, beat each other up in a heated Crisco fight on the kitchen floor, and left one another for dead.

A biopic of their career, produced by Three Legged Cowboy Pictures, is in the works and slated for 2023.

Brock Steam and Storm Mist spent most of their summers modeling for JC Penney when they weren’t working as weathermen at competing news channels. 

After a prevailing westerly wind dragged Storm from the comforts of his home in Milwaukee to the teeming pavements of New York, he knew he needed to perfect his poses and modeling prowess or he’d be swallowed up whole by the Big Apple’s very own Brock Steam.

Brock’s dimpled chin made women in the 5 boroughs swoon, getting each and every one of them wetter than a dish towel in a monsoon.

But when the mustached Storm debuted on CBS with his full poon broom, a Brock amnesia swept over the country causing him to lose his job.

To supplement his severance package, Brock started modeling and eventually Storm joined him out of weatherman solidarity. Even with Storm’s mustachelessness, he continued to get modeling gigs and women, but soon a snow storm would descend upon Manhattan—the 80s cocaine fad. Both men eventually chalked up expensive addictions, losing their jobs and subsequently the respect of the weatherman’s Association of Schenectady.

Later that year, Brock and Storm found work together as NBC’s first co-anchored Storm Team and were last seen standing near a large body of water during a heavy rainstorm, getting wet while dramatically battling 70mph winds. The two were allegedly swept out to sea after an attempt to bring “realism to weather reporting.”

In the end, their dream had been to demonstrate to TV audiences just how strong that invisible force, the wind, really was—to let people hear the noise that the wind made. This was their legacy, their finest contribution to meteorology—that is until Gail Winds hit the scene!

It was a Tuesday morning, 1961 in Mayfield. Beverly had a long list of calls to make, and friends to talk shit about.

Promptly at 9am, the gossip calls began, spreading like a wind-blown brushfire through the little suburb. 

First victim: Carole Wallingford, the target of her latest “worst-cook-ever” obsession. Beverly caught the ear of her sister Janet and told her all about Carole’s rancid Tuna casserole, that she affectionately called “crapperole.” She went on about how Carole tried to dress it up in a pretty rooster themed heat-resistant Pyrex dish, calling it “worthy of a 5-alarm fire.” 

Then it was on to calling her neighbor Jean to discuss the latest scandal involving Marie Crawford’s ethically challenged husband Hal, who was suddenly fired from his job at the Kirby vacuum cleaner company, where he was sucking up more than cigarette ashes from the office carpet. It seems like Hal “accidentally” swung the vacuum cleaner hose around to the company safe and sucked up a cool $40,000—landing him in the slammer where lots of extracurricular sucking took place. 

It was when Beverly saw him drive home in a new Chevrolet that her cuntennae went straight up, prompting her to call the FBI to report him. Yet his wife Marie was always her “favorite neighbor.” 

Last call was to Lucy Grant. This time to tell Lucy all about her plumber Benny who was apparently a gay fella with a penchants for using his rather long snake to unclog Carole’s husband’s toilet for the fifth time in a month. Beverly, who was widely known as the butt whisperer, when it came to spreading gay rumors, affectionately called Benny the “Scroto-Rooter man” —a well deserved title.

Well, her job and my job for the day is done. But hey! You didn’t hear this from me!

It was a thursday morning in 1967, and Leigh was having her Corn Flakes cereal. She wasn’t like the rest, or so she thought.

No. She didn’t want strawberries in her cereal like all the other housewives on Betsy Brown Circle.
Even though the packaging said “serving suggestion,” she wasn’t having any of that pressure in her life. She preferred blueberries and other things in her cereal. 

As she peered out the window, watching little Benny go to the first grade for the third time, she realized she needed to keep her life a secret from the kids. She made sure they were gone before pouring Elmer’s glue in her bowl.

You see, Leigh has a disorder that causes her to eat gross, inedible things. She often craved items such dirt, paper, cardboard, or anything else she can get her hands on, and now she’s progressed to those pasty ass chips.

On Betsy Brown Circle, nothing is ever what it seems, but it could be worse—She could be eating Grape Nuts.

On Mondays, every Monday without fail, Joan Lakeridge, Agnes Penney, Cynthia Lowell, and Lucinda Fry, gathered for soup and conversation. Agnes would break out her world famous tomato bisque, adding a dash of fresh herbs from the garden and a hint of cream—the women were simply astounded. The color always seemed to be a consistent bright red, bursting with just the right amount of zest and balanced with a delicate sweetness.

It was well-known that Agnes’s soup was made from the finest heirloom tomatoes, and cooked for several hours every Monday morning to bring out all the bright acidic flavors. 

Well, this satchel of bullcrap all went to shit when Lucinda (far right) snagged Agnes at the Shop Rite in aisle eleven, on Sunday afternoon, buying six cans of Campbell’s Tomato soup...on sale no less! 

To add to the tragedy, Agnes was also seen in aisle one, buying a Sara Lee frozen cheese cake—the one with the circular pattern on top, which she proudly passed as her own by transferring it to a her ceramic pie plate and smoothing out the lines on top, even adding an extra layer of cream cheese. Agnes’s time had come. The finest cook and baker on Minerva Lane was a fraud, a sham, a trickster, an outright pettifogger!

Even though Agnes buried the cans and packaging at the very bottom of her trash can, she couldn’t hide from the inquisitive and meddlesome Lucinda Fry. 

Even Agnes’s flower beds were plastic.

When you stoop down to fauxliage, can things get any worse?

Vanessa loved her kids to death, practically, but they were a rambunctious pair, tearing up the house and often ripping wallpaper off the walls for fun.

When Vanessa Harper discovered Old Fashioned cocktails at a dinner party, she had one just about every night to deal with her daughters’ constant breathing in and out….in and out.

She never did like those kids.

Jack suffers from a wide range of mama’s boy personality disorders, and has different Bell phones anytime she calls—No matter where he is.

His tan wall phone at the wood shop says “Sure, I have a moment to talk to my mom when she calls right at that perfect moment when I’m struggling with that fucking screw! Mom always calls at the best time, and I’m as cool, calm and collected as I can be!” At the wood shop, Jack loves to make his mom gifts every day, even though he left elementary school years ago.

His white table top phone, sitting perfectly perched above the kitchen banquette, gives him the confidence he needs to call his sister Clara, to remind her it was their mother’s birthday last week, all whilst clanking his empty coffee cup on the saucer, in a true “you’re a piece of shit” style. Jack never forgets his mom’s birthday. 

And last, his blue and powdery Slimline bedroom phone is right there when he needs to call mom to ask her which tie to wear with his grey blue slacks. 
But wait, what’s this? Jack’s wife is calling from her job at the school. 

It’s time for a call-waiting face-off!

Will Jack once again choose his mother like he always does?
Will Jack’s wife cut his dick off while he sleeps?

Call Bell Telephones and pick your favorite color, but never choose your mother over your wife. Or at least, never admit that you did!

His second apartment over the Hoover vacuum cleaner shop went slightly more in a “Mission” style, although he doesn’t like to admit that. At that point Frank Lloyd Right’s quarter sawn oak was his obsession—but not the architect. Frank Right was his partner at the time, and the oak was strong with that one. At least that’s what we’ve heard.

After years of dabbling in versatile styles, he finally settled on Mid Century Modern, Atomic, Bauhaus, and Brasília, while dating a Brazilian for authenticity—btw, also strong in the oak department.

Caroline knew Benny was good. She’s also heard he had a queer eye for the straight gal, so she put her fag swag in gear, and played him some Judy Garland the minute he came in to check out the space to provide a quote. He seemed to like Caroline.

After some cocktails to loosen Benny up, the two discussed some terms of enqueerment: 
“You decorate my house for free, and I’ll accompany you to operas, art openings, fundraisers—just about any time you need to convince a client you’re 300% gay.” 

Benny like the idea of being the weirdo with the beardo, and a lifelong deal was finally struck.

Carolyn loved to decorate, and that’s why she’s now at the Bellevue Mental Facility.

When Woolworth’s introduced their new line of “Fruit Festival” plastics, Carolyn lost her mind and single-handedly purchased every product in the collection. As long as it had fruit on it somewhere, it was game-on.

As if preparing for an apocalypse, she covered the toaster, the mixer, shelves, the bread box, chairs, her husband Hal, and, at one point, their cat. Hal kept checking for leaks in the roof wondering if Carolyn was expecting torrential rain in the home, but it all seemed fine. 

Then it happened, on a frantic school morning, Carolyn went to make toast for Bobby and failed to locate the toaster. She searched high and low, she cried and yelled at Bobby to help her—the pattern swirling and created a psychotic whirlwind of pears and cherries, as if a hundred fruit tarts had exploded. 

Carolyn finally succumbed to the millions of sweet prunus avium, suffocating her mind and consuming her suburban OCD. She drove Bobby to school and quickly tried to return all the plastic covers to Woolworths, but she didn’t have her receipt.

She screamed at the cashier, the manager and district manager. 
Store security descended on her like fruit flies, and soon Carolyn was on her way to the nearby nut house, where fruits and nuts lived together in a perfect festival of crazy.

Today, Carolyn’s jams and compotes can be found at the Vermont Country Store. Since cherries and pears have been discontinued from her product line, she is well again. 🍒

We won’t know until they deplane, and customs inspects Annisa’s Bags for missing bananas!

As Claude was about to tell Sarah where he planned on taking her for dinner later, Pierre butt in and asked Sarah if she wanted to go for a swim—a veritable carpe-scrotum, à la française.

But what gave Pierre the bon bons to make such a presumption?
Could it have been Claude’s inquisitive peak at Pierre’s grande baguette in the men’s bathroom earlier? Did he simply smell weakness and cheap American cologne on poor Claude?

Or, was it that Claude and Sarah were brother and sister? Yes. The two were on vacation to visit their European side of the family. Claude was hoping to capture a young French soldier, which was apparently easy to do. And, Sarah was hoping to have her first summer fling with a blonde man, 15 years her senior. 

Earlier at the bar, Pierre happened to “over-listen” to Claude and Sarah speaking, and was relieved that the handsome man beside her was no threat for his moulin to get rouge. And simultaneously, after a cocktail and night of French-Canadian tonsil hockey on the veranda, Pierre got to put his finger on it! A victory for the French, finally!

When Helen Fabre broke her ankle in what was reported as a bizarre typewriter accident, there was the sudden need for a new office manager.

In desperation, she attempted to type a letter to a client using her feet, and in the process twisted her ankle—an injury no one would ever see coming, despite choosing her words carefully. 

But Helen had serious bouncebackability, instead of taking time off to nurse her sprankle, she wheeled herself around the office on the chair, speeding down the halls, back and forth, while stretching the phone cord to its maximum. 

It was then that Helen’s fatal accident occurred, when the cord no longer held her back from plunging out the 3rd story office window.

Using the “live action” keyboard on the Smith and Corona was a useful feature, but Helen should have begged her boss for a $22 intercom system much much sooner.

R.I.P Helen Janine Carole Louise Fabré.

In a sleepy northern London suburb, nurse Mary LaFey’s night shift was made all the more interesting when George Devonshire was admitted to room 45 with an extra large cucumber up his arse.

After 14 years as a nurse in Kentish Town, Mary had seen just about everything, but this was a first. She had heard of sexual “deviants,” and now she’d finally met one, face-to-ass.

To say George was embarrassed was an understatement. Mary asked gently, with a pained look on her face, “how in the garden of hell did this happen?”

George answered...”at the market, dear lady. I’m the manager. I slipped and fell in the back room, right onto a crate of cucumbers.... and one of them went straight.......”

“Enough,” Mary interrupted. “That’s enough! We need to start the procedure now.”

They wheeled George into a darkly lit operating room next door.
The faint sounds of equipment buzzing and wheezing, a flickering yellow light, and Doctor Wells standing there in shock, ready to commence the extraction. 

Mary opened up the surgical equipment closet to reveal a highly effective piece of modern operating equipment—a Kirby vacuum cleaner, a known super-sucker, perfect for the vegextraction.

While the procedure was a success, it was said that no salad was eaten on that day in Kentish Town Hospital. None. 

Mary quit her job and took a position at the local pet shop, where she sold lots of gerbils, never making the connection. Good for dear Mary. It’s just better this way.

When you live in the sticks of New England in Connecticut, things like this give you joy. 
Timothy and I love cooking. Our area’s sole kitchen store closed just after the pandemic got into full swing and it saddened us. We went in there this afternoon and blew $250.00 on a cherry red Staub grill pan today, to support them and to make more great dinners for each other. Food really is the way to one’s heart. In an attempt to rid herself of the anguish associated with being a local Bingo celebrity, Doris Fulbright wrote her last fan letter whilst suffocating with the help of her Lady Braun Astronette.

Steeped in the dreary hills of Blackheath, Doris had won Bingo six weeks in a row and by this time had amassed over 3,000£, courtesy of an inside connection at the Lewisham Church of Ascension. 

Pastor O’Dale, an Irish choir leader transplanted from Dover, had been knockin’ bingo balls with Doris, in an attempt to keep her coming back to church, week-after-week. 
So, he painted the bingo balls with alternate sets of numbers, and announced them without any oversight, making Doris a winner every time, and a new sensation.

Raised in a decent Protestant family, Doris could no longer live with herself after her bingo/bango scenario with the pastor. Sitting at the kitchen table, crying, she plugged in the Astronette and covered her entire head with it, setting it to “roast,” and writing her last letter to a local fan:

“Dear Mary, thank you for your kind letter of congratulations on my recent extreme bingo winning streak. It would do me no good to further the lie at this point, as I’m just about to end my life via Lady Braun. After a brief period of introspection, I’ve decided that my intercourse remorse was weighing too heavily upon me. Also, I am not the winner you believe me to be. For this I’m truly repentant.”

Mary received the cryptic, letter three days later and cried, but that Sunday, the church was stunned. Doris showed up with the most amazing bouffant hair style ever seen. She stood at the front doors of the church and proclaimed her love for pastor Doyle, as the churchgoers clapped and wiped tears away. 

“Bingo!,” she thought, as she drove home. “Thank you, Lady Braun! You saved the day once again!”

Jo and Jan Montgomery were “never lonely,” and it wasn’t always so obvious why.

On a rainy morning back in 1962, in the small hamlet of Crestwood, Jo and Jan arrived at the photoshoot for their first album cover at a little studio on a cobblestone street in town. The twin girls were excited beyond words, but the rain ruined everything and required a whole new touch-up once they arrived.

Up until this time, the girls had done everything together and were a twinspiration to all. They even married a set of male twins, who could often not be told apart, all but for one feature Jan’s husband Marty was extremely proud of. Marty had three testicles. 

After a heavy shellacking of Aqua Net, to re-style the girls hair, they got into position and casually laid their heads together as Billy Walker, school yearbook photographer extraordinaire, fired off a round of photos. 

“Hold it right there! We got the money shot, girls! That’s it, stay exactly in that position! This looks great!,” Marty sang with enthusiasm. 

It was at that moment, Jan looked over and noticed the can of super glue they’d just sprayed on their coiffs. In tears, Jo and Jan left the studio, and walked home completely conjoined at the hair. 

Later that night, the girls were forced to sleep together with their husbands in the same bed. As they all rolled around in a confusing mess of limbs and bodies strewn about, Jan knew she had the right man when she felt Marty’s triplesac on her leg. 

For the next few nights, no one could ever be lonely with five testicles in the same bed. Lois eventually tried piping in music, hoping to bring life and zest into their otherwise dreadful office. All of a sudden, sales picked up, employees were more social, and sales were No.1 in their state.

Lois also began bringing in artichoke dip and tuna casseroles to the office, and SSPI hit its stride. Weeks later they discovered the computers were actually giant tape recorders, recording all the calls and revealing employees were having phone sex with potential clients.

One employee had phone sex right there at her desk, miraculously turning all the black and white equipment to living color.

Back in mid 60s, Earl always had new hobbies during the spring and summers to occupy his time after hunting season.

When Earl Montgomery’s friends heard what would be his new pastime, they were amazed at the creativity and skill he possessed.

Earl was working on a knitting technique that would weave hot dogs into blankets, duvets and scarves, and he was ready to meet the deadline for his first Christmas order, starting with family.

Aunt Jean would probably love a smokey 100% pure beef shawl, while Earl’s mom
would sashay down aisle 7 of the local Kroger in an oversized Kosher cable knit
scarf and hat set—hold the relish and mustard.

While Earl won’t recommend oversized frankfurters or kielbasa for intricate knits, he says he’s managed to crisscross 4-inch weenies into a lovely weinerschnitzel blanket for his sister’s daughter.

To learn more about how to make fashionable clothing from meat by-products, look for Better Homes & Garden’s 1967 cookbook issue—Earl’s in there peddling his wears.

While all the other kids got fruit juice in a colorful Dixie Cup, Tommy Larson got a cup full o’ nuthin’.

“Hey, Miss Walker. What about me?,” Tommy quipped curiously.

“Well, Tommy. You’ve been a spoiled little fuckwad all day today in class. Why don’t you go to the water fountain and have a sip of warm metallic water that’ll shoot you in the eye?”

Tommy Larson was from the rich side of town, with an entitlementality Miss Harrison couldn’t stomach. This was her way to demonstrate what it was like to be spoiled, and she called it part of her “GAP—Gratitude Adjustment Program.”

“So, Tommy, this is for that time you kicked Clara in the tits, and forced Jimmy to eat his own boogers alone during recess. I want to make sure everyone understands what it’s like to be left out.”

That night Tommy went home and cried to his mom, so she came back to the school the next day with a gallon of fruit juice and dumped it on Miss Harrison’s head.

“Some cautionary tales are better left for children’s books, Miss Harrison,” she said, as she poured the last few drops from the pitcher. “Nobody treats my Tommy like that!”

Miss Harrison and Mrs. Larson are now besties. The children are all behaved, and in recess all day long, mostly asleep. Miss Harrison had found the perfect solution to quiet the demons of unruly children—Vodka.

Recess is now known as “Happy Hour” at George Washington Elementary.

When Nan began playing with her organ on flight 744, all heads turned towards her in unison.

Nan’s musical stylings and organ versions of pop’s greatest hit parade, pleased and excited the group of men and women headed for Peru back in 1959.

Sadly, after 4 songs, no one could turn their heads back.

Norman Walters, seen with the dark rimmed glasses, was especially chuffed at Nan’s version of “Come Fly With Me” performed with the “accordion” setting, which added insult to his neck injury. 

Norm just hated the accordion sound, and soon threatened to open up the emergency door and jump out while singing “fly with me, float down to Peru, in llama land there's a one man band, and he'll toot his flute for you!” 

Nan had a solution! She called up the “flute” sound on the console and gave Norm her one-woman band version, as she opened the door for him and sucked him out, scowl and all.

It was windy in the cabin that afternoon, but the lesson learned by Northwest Airlines was to place Nan in the front of the cabin. It just seemed like the right thing to do!

It was the third album by the Colporteur Twins that caused the Osmonds great grief.

Shortly after Darlene Colporteur dipped the front of her head in a vat of acid, her sons Julius and Darius, with the aid of her brother Herb, a part-time hobbit impersonator, entered their local recording studio to record their third violation against humanity, “On Your Knees, Sinners.”

With outfits sewn from the souls of 20 Elvis impersonators, the family members, unable to explain their group’s “twin” name, set out to support their album with sold out shows in Gobblers Crossing, Alabama, and at the nearby Colchester Recycling Center.

On the title track “On Your Knees (Unless You’re Black),” the song borrows the melody directly from the DeFranco Family’s “Heartbeat,” and the lyrics from The Osmond’s hit “One Bad Apple.” This set off their record labels on a furious path to arrest the family, and did so while they feasted at their local Denny’s.

It seemed rules and laws didn’t apply to the family because Jesus would save them and forgive them, but all they left us was an unforgivable legacy of Bedazzled pant legs and white Capezios.

To this day, no one knows if they invented “spirit fingers,” or why they’re called the Colporteur Twins. If you have information on the matter, please report it to Bobby West at once!

June Wallace loved, loved, loved Harvey’s Bristol Cream!
But, it was Harvey’s pistol cream she loved most, and she wasn’t shy about it.

Besides being perfectly sedated on sherry nearly every day of her life, often dosing off at work at the real estate office, June was always stocking up on booze for the holidays, even when she already had six full cases at home.

With her sherry-glazed holiday recipes, she was a big hit at all the pot luck dinners, especially when the glaze was on her. That’s where Harvey Bellmonte comes in.

To be exact, it was a Tuesday night in a neighboring town of Leewood, when June arrived at Roy and Kenny’s apartment—her favorite gay friends.

There was Harvey, regional sales manager for Harvey’s Bristol Cream.
Noticing June had only four, bottles, Harvey offered her another, and a co-dependent love affair began.

While Roy and Kenny were serving the Baked Alaska in the living room, June and Harvey were baked in the kitchen, cooking up a pie in the pantry, up against a wall of Betty Cocker cake mix, and various soup. Harvey wanted to make brownies, but June rejected his advances, so the two settled for a quickie and his famous pistol cream chaser.

After ten years of marriage, the holidays are still extra fun for June, who toggles between work, the liquor store, and dialysis. 

It’s always a creamy white Christmas at Harvey and June’s!

When Lucas and Jenny went to the school the next day, they landed in principal Walker’s office for using profanities.

“Tubesteak Tarzan,” “donut puncher,” and “butt burglar,” were just a few of the gems the kids heard on that fateful night. It was the night of uncle Hal’s 40th birthday.

Being gay meant that all bets were off when it came to controlling uncle Hal’s lack of conservatism. Hal had a lust for life, a joie de vivre, a serious case of vagina declinin’, and it was all holds barred when it came to late night storytelling.

That night, Lucas and Jenny heard all about uncle Hal’s vacation to the Keys, back in ’58, when his partner Bud “slipped on a zucchini” and had to be taken to the emergency room for vegetative extraction. And, that time at his sister’s wedding at the Elk’s Lodge, when Hal’s buttplug popped out on the dance floor during Little Richard’s “Tutti Frutti.”

The kids finally realized uncle Hal was gayer than a handbag full of rainbows—an inspiration to be just as you are. In fact, they couldn’t wait to boost their vocabulary every time the “fun uncles” came to visit.

Later on, in high school, Lucas came to school wearing a boa, high heels, and face full of rouge. It wasn’t Halloween.

“Of course gay people dress well! We didn’t spend all that time in the closet doing nothing!,” Lucas told his teacher.

Jenny always knew her brother was special. So after college and settling down with her family, she wrote a novel “Lessons From the Staircase.”
The dedication read “A lot of parents do everything for their kids, except let them be themselves. Thanks, uncle Hal (1927-1972).”

It was 1976. Jackie, Chad and Sally went for a morning run in Beverly Hills on a perfect Thursday morning.

Suddenly, from behind a bush, a photographer from Nut Smuggler Magazine happened to catch Chad and the girls in captivating poses, just before they all burst into flames from breaking a sweat.

Chad (a Gordon Ramsey and Lee Majors love-child) looked ravishing in his cute little outfit as it perfectly silhouetted his Bone Ranger lunchbox. Meanwhile, the girls rocked their camel-toe track shorts like nobody’s business. When Chad and the girls clenched their fists, the photographer knew this fierce little workout/impromptu photo-sesh, would make it to the centerfold.

After the shoot, the Three’s Company trio headed back to their wicker explosion at the condo, ready to rest up for an afternoon of roller skating and unprotected sex––of course not with each other, cuz that would just be gross for Chad. But, at the end of the day, a day filled with “strenuous” activities for this sunny California trio, their expended calorie count was a total of three.

Ben Flamingo (back left) and his gang “The Fondudes”were never less than a block away from trouble.

After a night of dancing at the Manroot Men’s Social Club, poor Lenny Shasta, was walking home singing Neil Sedaka’s “Breaking Up is Hard To Do,” as happy and go lucky as any gay boy could be. He wasn’t hard to spot with that newly dyed blonde coif, created by his aunt Jeannie earlier that evening. Aunt Jeannie knew Lenny was a dick gobbler, and accepted him just the way he was. She wanted to make sure her favorite nephew shined like a tiara in that club. She put out her cigarette and kissed Lenny on the forehead and whispered “you go get ‘em, Tiger!”

But that evening, The Fondudes just happened to be hunting tigers with fancy hair. Ben caught a flicker of blonde shimmers 50 yards away, noticed Lenny’s sashay, and that saccharine sweet melody. Man, did Ben hate Neil Sedaka.

Lenny looked back, hearing the whispers behind him, then suddenly, he saw the three thugs approach him with increasing speed. He walked faster and faster, little sparks flying out his butt, he quickly ducked into the back alley doorway of King Chow’s Chinese restaurant. But there they were, seething with disdain — Ben, Jimmy, and Bruce (far right).

Ben gently pushed Lenny up against the crumbling brick facade, “what are you doing here, kid? Shouldn’t you be at home unscrewing the toothpaste?,” he asked in a deep threatening voice. “Why, I’m just walking home, minding my own business. What’s it to ya?,” Lenny asked quivering. “Bruce here would like to ask you a damn question, shut your mangina.”

Bruce shuffled through, stepped up to Lenny, just inches from his sweaty face and asked, “uhm, yeah, you free to go to the spaghetti dinner with me at St. Luke’s church 7pm on Friday?”

“Why yes” Lenny jumped enthusiastically. “Uhm.....can I bring my Aunt Jeannie.”

The Fondudes looked at each other, tilted their heads in unison and nodded in accord.
“Yeah, yeah, man. That’s cool.” Lenny said.

The four talked about hair products and gels for some time, quickly dispersing when the local police arrived about a disturbance behind King Chow’s.

They were all clearly born to be gay.

When Jeannette saw her sister Sandrine’s child for the first time, her heart stopped, and not in a good way.

Newly born Colette was quite freakish, and Jeannette had never developed acting skills well enough not to show her shock. She uttered “poor child” under her breath, luckily out of her mother’s earshot.

Colette was simply not the most beautiful child. Her face resembled a cross between Napoleon and Iggy Pop. This was not a good look.

While Sandrine tried all the tricks to make her baby look beautiful, from bonnets to bows, florals to classic French stripes—nothing helped poor Colette look less like a foot.

Jeanette later compared her to a “plate of dropped escargot,” but still showered Colette with love, and gifts, and compliments. It was the right thing to do.

When Colette grew up and stopped chasing parked buses, she eventually developed a look that was described by her mother as “exotic” and “cute as a bunny,” while others in school simply called her Fugs Bunny. Kids can be so cruel.

Colette is now a Ford model. Go figure.

After a brief stay in Westchester Country Hospital with third degree burns to her scalp, forehead, chin and neck, Lenore Kravits vowed never to go to her friend Kenny’s Trinidadian themed parties again.

It was the Tiki craze of 1958 that swept through the suburbs of New York, like a straw broom, and Lenore, an Arthur Murray School of Dance student thought she could Limbo her ass under the very lowest rung, but never made it.

After the third rung, Lenore was feeling like an authentic native from Trinidad, despite her firm roots in Scarsdale, but sadly her back gave way, and then the fire started, to the tune of “Donkey Want Water”

This prompted her “best friends” Sarah and Norman, well-known provocateurs and troublemakers, to hose down Lenore’s head, saving  her life, after an hour of chanting and egging her on. They’d never get involved in such low class behavior anyway. 

As it would turn out, Lenore never went to the Caribbean, and Calypso music made her shudder, but she’s still got freaky in the bedroom with Jack, the man on the left, whom she married.

Jack loves Lenore, despite the monthly visit from Father McLeary who performs an exorcism to get her spine realigned, and to stop her head from spinning—but she’s all good now.

There’s always more to a picture than meets eye, despite a singed eyebrow.

Bobby’s PSA: 
This makes me wonder where and why it all went wrong. How did we let it go so very astray. How very dare us! And, this goes for men as well!
I can’t believe people dress like this and go out in public looking like Sharkanado got to their wardrobe. 

Call me old-fashioned. But, this isn’t any kind of fashion, is it? It’s almost like the end of fashion. It’s the end of the sensible pant suit, the stylish pleated skirt, the floral print, and for men, the suit and tie, and stylish hats and well-made shoes. 

As a mid-century lover, we need more people to go back, way back to a day when going out in public meant that every aspect of life was a blessing to participate in. That every moment with friends and family is a celebration. Where “dressing up” meant confidence and good taste.

Leggings, ripped jeans, men’s sweats, and athletic wear is fine coming and going to the gym, but at a restaurant, make an effort, for fuxx sake. Especially guys who wear baseball caps and NRA shirts to dinner.

The golden age of travel was a time when stepping out of the home, going to an airport, and on a plane was an expression of our collective respect for one another, not looking like you opened the cabin door at 3,000 feet and got your clothes torn off! 

Honestly, dressing like a pauper is an expression of laziness, deference, and apathy, and also an act of counter culture.

Now, I am all about “live and let live!” But, if I’m describing you and this offends you, you have my deepest apologies. But we are all adults here. Most of you followed me for the last 4 years because we all share a love for a magical time in our country’s history.

LoveMidCentury65 is not just an Instagram account. It’s a command. 😂 To “love” the period is to “live” the period. Dressing in period style, dressing ⬆️ , expressing your love for anything midcentury in every small way, whether it’s your love of Tiki culture, 50s tailoring, or by buying cool MCM furniture, you are the growing and most popular trend in the country. 

So, keep that up. Stay stylish and throw out the distressed jeans FFS. It looks like you might have lost your job and your dignity. Everyone likes nice things, right?

By now, Ol’ Man Grady had gotten a bit crabby of all the needy tourists at his Lobstah Shanty in Portland, Maine.

Jean McCluire who was terrified of old crustaceans, was equally terrified of lobster, especially those gripping robstah craws being shoved in her face.

She commented that she didn’t serve crabs or lobster at her restaurant in Connecticut for the same reason. But Peggy, on the other hand, just adored the creatures, and photographed them everywhere the lesbian couple travelled.

During this episode of Jean & Peggy’s New England Vajourney, poor Grady, while toying with the young couple, got bitten in the lobsticle by a feisty little one-pound cock lobster. Jean, the feisty one blurted, “well isn’t that just a little bit of Karma, coming your way, sir?”

The old man was impressed at how snippy the young lady was and asked, “Do you happen to have a bar in your restaurant back home?”
Jean answered firmly, “why no, sir.”—tilting her head in confusion.

“Well, you should apply for a lickher license soon!,” turning around and snickering with pride.

It wasn’t until the doughnut bumpers reached the bus, that Jean looked at Peggy, with mouth agape, and finally got it.

It was clear, no one could match witts or clits with Ol’ Man Grady!

Darren Wilson loved his freakish sister Janine with all his heart, except for that one time when she pee’d in his brand new wagon.

It was a typical summer Monday in Maytown. Mom had just made breakfast, and dad had gone off to work at the chocolate plant in Hershey. Darren loved to make his sister laugh and take her for long rides down Maple then Myrtle Avenues, but her love of orange juice was undeniable.

Bump after bump, Janine tried to hold her pee in, but a trickle turned into a full-on supersoaker, as golden splashes of piss filled the interior of the wagon and landed on Darren’s hand.

Darren laughed as their dog Jax crapped loafs all up and down Midland, landing turdlettes squarely on everyone’s lawn. This is how the Wilsons marked their territory all over the neighborhood.

When Darren arrived back at home, Jax the dog was chasing Darren, but the wagon was empty. In a panic, Mom asked Darren what happened to his sister, and he replied “She opened up a lemonade stand at Aunt Clara’s!” 

Darren was punished and had to stay up in his room all day for actually leaving his sister with a soaked dress at the bottom of the hill. 

When he ran to the bathroom to strain his noodle there was a sign on the door that read: “Bathroom closed for repairs. Please use your wagon.” 

Mom had a sense of humor alright. She was a real pisser!

Gene and Margaret were married for thirteen years and loved giving each other surprise gifts for no particular reason .

When Gene received a flat box he silently thought “shit, another shirt!”
Welp, he was right. It’s not only a shirt, it was another blue shirt!
But, the young couple seemed to be in a long-standing silent competition.
Every year for Christmas, Margaret received a toaster, or a vacuum, and last year she received a blender—appliances designed to keep the “little missus” busy at home in compliant lockstep.

It was only fair that Margaret gave Gene a taste of his own misogyny.
Problem was, his gifts kept Margaret working, and her gifts kept him looking
well-dressed and dapper. Things were askew, and surely, there would need to be a switch-up in Margaret’s game.

This Christmas, Gene will receive 20 gallons of paint, paintbrushes, a ladder and a roller. Margaret calls it dad’s “prize package!” Safe to say, he’ll need to wear an old shirt and ripped jeans (ha!) when painting the entire house.

Hhhhmmmm, Margaret is definitely onto something!
The way it should be. Give people a chance. Let them find the right path and accept them back into your heart. It’s the only way. #happypeidemonth❤️💛💚💙💜

Harry was a seasoned waiter who’d seen it all. Any time good looking men came to the famous Rear Admiral Seaside Restaurant, he always needed to figure them out. He was an avid eavesdropper who loved to people watch and to play little detective games.

Meanwhile, Luke and Dorian were enjoying several cocktails and fun conversation. By 2pm, the two were doodling incoherently, and acting gayer than Liberace’s fanny pack. For Harry, it was confirmed the boys worshipped at the church of Latter Gay Saints. He knew he’d leave his shift with the best stories he’d ever hear.

At the end of their happy hour, Harry learned that the two men were actually brothers. They were both married to women, and in the carpentry business, visiting for two weeks from Sweden. This was not what Harry expected at all.

Welp, that explains it! Harry’s gaydar needed some serious dusting and electrical work. His ability to distinguish between gay or European was now severely compromised.

Soon his yearly summer job at the Rear Admiral would end. The restaurant would close down for the winter, and his life would change once again, as it had for over 30 years.

It was the end of another summer of youthfulness, new acquaintances, cocktails and salty air, soon to be followed by another long, lonely winter in his basement rental, in a cold New England town.

They did, but Margaret Hackney’s cellophane-fresh wrap had some issues.

Beth Markovich loved Mrs. Hackney and humored her, no matter what she said, never knowing if she was joking or not. 

In fact, Mrs. Hackney was the funniest, oldest, and most God-fearing woman in the town of Crestwood. She’d always say “I’d rather be judged by 12 than carried by 6!” After losing her husband Jerry in 1952, she wanted to stick around and visit his grave to tell him jokes. 

But one day at the supermarket she proclaimed to her neighbor Beth, “when I pass, do like they do with all these vegetables, Bethy, and make sure they seal me in cellophane! I want the finest and thickest Cellophane they have!” Well, as any coroner would tell you, it wasn’t pretty. 

When she passed at the mature age of 96, Mrs. Hackney was indeed wrapped in plastic. Right there, underneath her “pinewood overcoat” was a Cellophane-Fresh, hermetically-sealed woman. At least they thought.

Actually, Mrs. Hackney was joking all along, and as you suspected, the cellophane did very little to preserve the funniest ol’ lady on Minerva Lane. But, it was always her goal to die young as late as possible, and that she did!

On Sundays, the McKenzie’s gather round the new Zenith TV to watch a blank screen.

While the family has always had difficulty making choices, now they rely on their active imaginations to bring them their favorite programs.

In their minds, little Christine is watching The Flintstones; Jerry is enjoying The Andy Griffith Show; Mom is watching cooking with Julia Child, and dad is enjoying “Leave It In Her Beaver”, which is why he’s always using the newspaper to shield his groinal regions.

Before there were 300 cable channels, there were only 6 or 8 channels, and life was much less complicated.

Maybe when dad can get up, without a boner, he can plug the TV in!

Back in 1965, Jeanine wasn’t very good at modeling. She was always tripping on the runway, burning herself in kitchen scenes, and seen here, spraying perfume directly into her eye.

After several attempts to rinse out her inflamed eye, the director decided to send her home. Jeanine fell into the pit of despair, canvassing stores for work, and filling out applications with that one good eye, rarely writing the address perfectly on the provided lines. One employer marked her “unemployable due to excessive winking,” which also caused sexual harassment claims against her, as she seemed to be flirting with all the young men, including the 16 year-old mail boy.

Poor Jeanine couldn’t get a break, except for last week when she actually broke her chin miscalculating the revolving door at Macy’s. When her eye partially healed in 1967, Jeanine landed a job as a stewardess but was discouraged from demonstrating the oxygen mask for fear of self -strangulation.

Moral of this story: Don’t be like Jeanine and spray perfume into your eye. Truly bad shit will happen!

Jane wanted Tex. Tex wanted to decorate. Holy Sears Roebuck, Houston, we have a problem!

When Jane invited Tex over for coffee and a quick shag, she discovered his interest lie on the living room walls, and not on the boudoir bed, as she had planned.

She tempted him with decaf, threw off her shoes, bent over backwards, literally, to tempt his libido, but Tex was concerned with the placement of a new esoteric “painting” Jane just purchased at Woolworth’s.

Tex had no aversion to department store art, and even complimented Jane’s dress confirming it did indeed matched the JC Penney pillow, but her painting had too much green and well, Tex just hate, hate, hated it!

But what could she do to get Tex to re-focus his glandular attentions back to her.

It appears nothing would convince Tex, a certified Tubesteak Tarzan (not that there’s anything wrong with that), to hit on Jane.

After 14 years of futility wrapped in chenille, it was obvious Tex was straight as a rainbow. So, Jane gave up on her longtime Crisco Cowboy, finally marrying a man that used power tools for actual work, who loved NASCAR and hunting, and occasionally some Quiche Lorraine, (not that there’s anything wrong with that!).
Grant and Theadora didn’t mind the sea salt and crabs nipping at their heels. They had more money than God and didn’t care that their Broyhill furniture would get ruined. Money is no object.

Jeremy and his wife Sofia had been married for 6 years when he finally broke the news to her at the J'aime Les Hommes Café in Paris. 

At the local gym close to their hotel, Jeremy had been engaging in extremely “low fidelity” activities, working out his organ with a fitness trainer named Henri.

Squat after squat, Jeremy’s ass cheeks became more supple and more desirable to Henri, and that’s where the trouble began. Henri’s full body training regiment ensured that Jeremy’s tight little moulin rouge was be redder and more milled than he could imagine. 

In fact, Jeremy would wake up in the middle of the night and visit Henri while Sofia “slept,” and every morning she notice he’d been in a great mood.

One morning over espresso and Madeleines, Sofia asked where he’d been the last six nights, to which he replied, “well, dear. I’ve been trying to keep it like, super gay for a while now.” 
Sofia replied, “well, I guess I have news too. I have been meeting up withClaire the hotel concierge every evening as well!”

The two laughed it off and switched from coffee to wine as Jeremy and both Sofia released a sigh.
Perhaps a ménage a trois with Henri or Claire, was in order?

Many exciting conversations were had that morning, but soon they’d return to the states, where the two would be ostracized from humanity and their favorite album “Keep It Gay” headed for the local burn pile. But that’s a whole other conversation!
