Delores Whithurst just had the week from hell. Suddenly, all of her hopes, dreams and plans were cancelled.

The trip to Norway, the leather luggage, the dreams of meeting with her long-lost love Erik—all gone. How could Delores go on?

When the flu of ‘57 spread throughout Europe, travel bans and self-quarantine kept Delores and her mother at home for weeks, playing bridge and drinking untold gallons of Earl Grey tea.

She could no longer play tennis with Sara Watkins and Glendora Pruise. The Ladies Auxiliary of Larchmont shuttered indefinitely. Her staff, Rosario, Belinda, Maria, Hector, Louis, all of them, let go. The Tulip Club reduced to mounds of dirt.

With a mask and gloves Delores braved the pandemic and went to the local Shop-Rite for more “Social Tea” biscuits. This was her comfort food. This and an occasional spoon of caviar, but the shelves were barren. All the best caviar wiped out.

When a beggar arrived at Delores’ front step, she recoiled and shuttered the entire home, calling the police. How could they assault her in such a way during a stressful time—a time of inconceivable loss.

Delores and her mother Jean continued playing bridge into the night, waiting for a sign that things would go back to “normal.” 

The next day Delores checked with her stock broker, the market had recovered, and the Whithurst fortune was fully restored from 60 million to 72 million. Good thing she had stock in pharmaceuticals.

Another tragedy had befallen Larchmont, but Delores rose from the golden ashes, as she always could. The shelves were once again restored, the staff rehired.

Oh, glory days were here again.

Brenda loved her twin sister, until that morning when she was convinced by Laura that brushing her hair with 1000 strokes every day would make it stronger and shinier. 

Laura brushed Brenda’s hair vigorously, until all of it fell out. 

Then, without warning, Laura got kicked in the hoo-ha, and it was clear—nobody was twinning on that fateful Monday morning.

It was only a matter of time until the Ump and Batter blew their stacks and settled their differences.

Back in 1958, there was the “Gay Baseball League of Kansas,” where players wore a “Special K” on their uniforms and pranced about the baseball field in true brotherhood, purposely hitting balls into the corn field. 

At any given time during a ball game, one of the players would walk out of the field of cream, with a sheepish smile on their face. The Ump, would reprimand any player who’d hit a foul ball by asking him to retrieve it. It was there among the corn that the ump would pop his sugar all over the batter, and eventually frost his flakes. 

That, friends, is the real history of how “Frosted Flakes” and “Sugar Pops” came about— a little known Kellogg’s secret.

Whichever you choose, variety is always the spice of life. 

Whether, you’re a pitcher or catcher, shortstop, backstop, or switch hitter, versatility will ensure you a spot on the bench of this incredibly gay team—and that was a good thing. 

Either way, your bat’s would see lots of play, and someone always ended up with little milk on their upper lip!

Hola! It’s Fiesta Del Monte at the local supermarket in Crestwood, circa 1962. 

No matter how Jennifer Martin tries to avoid Shirley Bayer, there she is, popping up like a loonbag at Jennifer’s hair salon, at her job at the library, and here at the Supermarket, where oddly they only sell DelMonte products. 

After Shirley had a nervous breakdown and spent time in jail for leaving her unoccupied car running in the garage, while her family was home, (oops)—people have been avoiding her like a mild case of flesh-eating bacteria. 

The local police have kept tabs on Shirley for some time now, and if she slips up one more time, she be spending her Fiesta Del Monte at the Casa Del Coo-Coo for stalking Jennifer, never mind attempted murder. 

You know, it’s all fun and games until Jennifer hurls a can of tuna at Shirley from aisle three!

Sarah and Bill stopped off for a quick oil change, and a mild roasting at the DX Firestone station.
 
Confused about all the types of oil viscosities, Bill tried being polite, listening intently as the perplexing overhead french fry heaters, caused Bill to spontaneously combust as his pubes suddenly caught on fire.

Bill immediately “stopped, dropped and rolled,” putting out the fire in his crotchal area, while he vowed never to return to this awful place.

Lesson learned: When visiting any roadside quick-fire roasting station, always be sure to wear protective head gear.

Sixty color swatches later, DeAnne finally found the right green!
It was a green spool of thread that her mom had in a seashell sewing box that sat on her dresser for ages.

Jerry himself of Jerry’s Painting of Larchmont was flummoxed, and maybe a little drunk, to say the least.

His client Annabel Whitlock was an ambitchious, overly-dramatic young woman who only spoke Biotchenese, and wanted the home to reflect her most modern and trendy cuntabilities.

Don’t get me wrong, she had vision and focus, but DeAnne just drank a full glass of haterade and used her resting bitch voice to let Jerry know he missed the mark once again.

Having had 5 gallons of enough is enough, Jerry decided to lose his cool, and his career in painting, by painting DeAnne in a trendy green stripe that started from her forehead down to her gold Dior belt buckle.

Jerry was readily promoted to fired, and released from his duties in what was considered a vocational paradigm shift like none he’d ever experienced.

A few days later at the Supermarket, when Jerry was retrieving shopping carts from the parking lot for $2.00 an hour, he saw DeAnne’s green car. He shouted “That was it! That was the color she wanted all along!”

Jerry, the former painter, pulled back the shopping cart, once, twice, three times, revving up to what would be a high speed shove of incredible force and trajectory.

He yelled “I hate you, green!” as the cart careened 30 miles an hour right into DeAnne’s Ford Falcon.
Bam!

From plastered painter, to soft core shopping cart terrorist, life in suburbia is never as dull as some may think!

A Mid-Century Night’s Dream! 

It’s Wednesday night in a California suburb, circa 1964. A clear blue sky illuminates the suburban landscape on Betsy Brown Circle. 

You can see the glowing yellow lights as you turn off from Crestview Lane, and as you arrive, the faint sweeping orchestral melodies of Les Baxter’s “Space Escapade” wafts through the air. 

A tuna casserole is in the oven and will soon be proudly served in your favorite orange Corning dish.

But first, it’s time for that after-work cocktail. The weekend  approaches, and it’s not quite time for a Mai Tai, but a Manhattan will do the trick. 

Just like that, it seems, all your troubles melt away. 

#1960s

“Brrrrrrrr, it’s cold out here. Better go inside and warm up with some minced meat” said no one ever!

Laura’s steaming pile of poop covered in smashed potatoes was an igloo no staving Eskimo would ever eat—even if it was the last meal on earth.

Living in anchorage for the Davis Family meant everything was Alaskan themed and usually adorned with Kale, once used for decorating various lunch platters at the Sears Luncheonette. A melted slice of Kraft cheese assured everyone at Laura’s table she had no idea what the fuck she was doing.

But still, she tried. At least it was better than a poke in the eye with an ice pick.

It seemed no one ever made the “mmmm” sound, no one commented. Year after year Laura presented the family with her “Arctic Blast” meatcake which resulted in a running competition for the igloo back house.

If you ever intend on making this mince meat murder pile, with fake shrubs that could never survive a Alaskan weather, please do not invite Bobby West!

She went into a long momologue about how she was just trying to help, so it was time to shove his favorite screaming banshee from hell down a flight of stairs into the specially built “suite” —replete with padded and sound proof walls, a transistor radio, and a stack of automobile magazines in hopes she’d steer her way clear out of their lives!

Janice Westport was a horrible, horrible cook with ginormous cuffs. When she said “Come and get ‘em,” she may have been a tad early.

During a Memorial Day party, Janice finally ventured into the world of grilling, putting her Crock Pot to rest for a weekend.

First, it was young Jeffrey who yarfed a solid burger clear across the jail-styled block wall into the Miller’s yard. Then suddenly, sweet Marla ran into the house to have a quick chat on the “big white phone.” Soon the whole family jumped in the Ford Country Squire and headed straight for Westchester General Hospital to have their stomachs pumped. Janice is no longer hosting barbecues on grills without flames, and is now back in the kitchen making beef stew and cooking things for 8 hours or longer.

Keep that shit up, Janice!

When Doris wasn’t busy basting her thighs, she was discovering new and creative ways to excite her husband Robert, seen doing some buttering up of his own to Doris’ mom and grandma.

It was the weekend that Harry Morgan from next door brought over his rotisserie chicken cooker, that “home kinks” went from kinky to kinktastic.

Doris asked Harry if he could build a rotisserie on a larger scale, and deliver it to the basement of her home for Robert’s 30th birthday.

All the fuckoutrements, from whips to hog ties, and leather straps were easily available for Robert as Doris spun dizzyingly, dripping in various sauces.

It was a Tied-Up Tuesday in an unsuspecting home, on a quiet street in Midville, Ohio.

Dinner’s ready!

Mary made it a tradition of inviting Carole over for morning coffee every day, especially Sundays. After Mary’s husband died in a bizarre gardening accident, she was alone and always sought company, especially in the mornings when she felt most vulnerable.
On this morning, Carole was busy with her own husband Ken, who was attaching the summer window screens, while Carole beat the balls out of the carpets with a giant egg beater.

A perfect cup of java had just finished percolating, and Mary considered herself a procaffeinator like no other. It was her drug. A panacea of sorts—there to help her deal with her loneliness.

If she were still alive today, she’s have none of this pumpkin spice latte bullshit.
She was a woman who loved her coffee with that good to the last drop flavor.

Truth is, she needed coffee to poop. And the last “drop” meant something completely different to Mary! If she didn’t have her coffee at 7am, she’d be stopped-up like a cork in a bottle of Kahlúa for the whole day!

Mary was admittedly a caffeind, and Carole was her best next door java junkie.

The two sipped and quipped well into their 70s and coffee was forever a part of their friendship.

With that said, time for Bobby to have a crappuccino!

After causing several accidents on the Merritt Parkway, Loraine’s back tire finally gave out. Sadly for Loraine, she had no idea what a jack looked like, much less know how to use one.

As she pumped and pumped, a few more heads turned and more motorists crashed into trees, embankments and each other. One motorist flew clear across the median and ended up in someone’s backyard while they were enjoying a Columbus Day barbecue.

Then suddenly, as the wind swept her dress up unexpectedly, a nearby police officer who had just happened upon the scene, passed out as he caught a glimpse of Lorraine’s sexy underwear. Poor guy never stood a chance, as he too joined the massive heap of wreckage.

Luckily, no one died that day, but Lorraine was escorted to the police station and kindly asked never to wear that dress again.

Lorraine, of course, wore it again the very next day!

The Harlem-based group “This Dick,” belongs in the where-are-they-now-files, yet, leave it up to me to dig them out.

When Dwayne, Jermaine, and Rickey formed This Dick, previously Deez Nuts, in Harlem 1967, it was clear their manager, and seamstress Shirley Jackson had a clear-cut vision, and a fast track to inevitable disaster. But, it wasn’t just their denim explosion that caused their split.

In the mid 70s, their music reviews were brutal. Rolling Stone wrote, “a cross between Stevie Wonder and a thousand screaming whistle kids,” while Jet Magazine quipped, “Earth, Wind and Fire just changed their name to ‘Scorched Earth, Ass-wind, and FireBomb”. But, none was more heartless and insulting than AfroJam Magazine’s review; “...for an all black band, they’ve got the rhythm of a three-legged coffee table tumbling down six flights of stairs in a Harlem project.” 

But the whole mess finally fell apart during this exact photoshoot. Rickey(right) was down to his last good nerve. Even though the photographer asked the guys to make believe a hot mamma was passing by, Rickey, clearly not the cooperative dude in the band, said “bitch, I will cut you. Rickey don’t play make-believe. I keeps shit real.” Rickey forgot the photographer was Jermaine’s cousin, and this pushed Jermaine to his own realness limit, wrestling Rickey to the ground, ending in a blood-soaked tangle of blue jeans and flaired collars that permanently ended This Dick.

Seems like it never ends well for bands here on LoveMidcentury65!

This little gathering at Dayton International Airport is not what it seems. 

You see, this band of dreamers aren’t actually traveling anywhere. 

On Saturday nights, back in 1961, this gang of friends would dress in their best outfits and gather in the airport lounge to watch American Airlines’ brand new jets take flight while sipping Whiskey Sours and gossiping about their well-to-do neighbors. Darlene (second from left), is just about to reveal her neighbor Sarah has just had plastic surgery that has got her looking perpetually frightened. 

Erica (far right) is spilling the beans on her stock broker neighbor, Mark Farrington, and his love affair with another man at the Pheasant Hill barber shop. And the men, who claim to “never gossip”—they enjoy every scandalous word with delight. 

No one on the security team has caught on that they don’t have real flights to get on, and are merely pretending to be world-class travelers, so they tempt fate every week. 

On Mondays, the band of long time friends all go back to their perfectly ordinary lives — the men to the Five Oaks Sanitation department, and the women to the cosmetic counter at the nearby Woolworths. I guess they can be whomever they want and dream that suburban “American Dream.” 

When they’re at the airport lounge, on flight 707 to nowhere, all bets are off!

As a devout atheist, little William Cooper(Back) distanced himself from his family as they went from home to home, trying to proselytute themselves in the name of God. 

While his siblings rejoiced in being the children of God, their parents Sarah and Joseph, were constantly busy sewing outfits for family photos on their ‘76 Christploitation Tour. 

The fact that they dressed the same was a testament to the idea that none shall stand out or be different.

But, William always made sure the world knew that he was not Mormonic like them, especially when they walked the neighborhood and posed for photos in stranger’s living rooms. 

At 18, William was somewhat of an oxy-mormon—a rebellious and pot smoking child who eventually came out of the closet, renounced his religion, cast sweater vests out of his wardrobe, and went from Mormon to Moremen.

Good for you, Billy. What’s the use in being “God’s child” when he only served you the Fruit Loops for breakfast? He had a plan for you all along.

Harrison was not one to ask for directions, so they ended up in Maine, when they were actually attempting a trip to Hershey, Pennsylvania.

Mary finally strapped on her best smile and turned off the vehicle while they were driving, coming to a dead stop on the side of Route 1.

Harrison considered it the same stubborn trait as his dad, but Mary simply chalked it up to certified insanity. It had been a long day, filled with frustrating diversions and unintended visits to relatives they didn’t even have.

It was the final straw when Harrison pulled into a stranger’s driveway, and yelled “first ones here!,” that the kids realized that dad needed an intervention.

Harrison’s toxic stubbornness and mangenuity had literally gotten them nowhere and ruined their lives.

Luckily, the kind man at the Esso in Portland led the family back on track and pointed them in the right direction, but it was only then the family kept on going north to Canada, and never looked back.

Besides, their son Bud really loved hockey, Tim Horton’s and milk by the bag.

It was a natural decision.

Back in ‘73, Stockholm’s greatest music export was Martys. There were six brothers, plus another three they couldn’t fit on the cover.

It was obvious that Sven and Hans were the two brother packing serious snacks in their slacks. So Bjorn, the photographer, asked for them to stand up front to highlight their left-sided ballsack tacos.

At their live shows, girls swayed and swooned, and the gay men swayed Sven and Hans to meet them backstage after the show—for which they oddly obliged. Hey, it’s Europe. In the seventies. Don’t judge.

After some quick manual labor in the dressing room, the two men emerged red faced and satisfied. Their swedish meatballs plump and ready for their next shoot.

It’s not widely known that Theo, Axel and Franz, the seldom seen band members, died suddenly in a freak IKEA accident, trying to assemble a very large Flargshnorfin bookcase. But the remaining brothers sing in remembrance of their brethren.

This album, “3” is a deadication to the three brothers, but it’s also the amount of the 3 million dollar settlement the boys received for the Wonkea disaster!

Did you know?? That’s right your buddy Bobby has a secret gig designing various things over 20 years for the iconic Beatle. I’ve never made that public because it’s just something that I held dearly.

But meeting him several times at his office, and seeing how he marked up my artwork, and the hundreds of graphics I’ve done through the years has made me super proud of my work for him. It’s slowed down quite a bit in the last few years. But we’re still active and my work is still active and widely used. Just being associated with a Beatle is the stuff of dreams. 

My Beatles and Paul McCartney experience with my husband at the beginning of our relationship was magical, we spent a week in London walking on clouds after landing the gig, then flying over and visiting John and Paul’s homes, Strawberry Fields, as well as Penny Lane, the Cavern and the Liverpool museum was surreal. We hired a classic black taxi to take us around the whole rainy morning. It was as English as you’d imagine.

The Abbey Road Studios part of the trip was mind blowing. Getting to see the studios with a private tour, and seeing the piano and organ used in Let It Be, the control room and the view down to the main room was transcendent. Just to be in that room l, wow! Sadly, we couldn’t take photos because there was an orchestra recording at the time. But the one shot I did get inside, I lost in a fried hard drive incident. 

I wish I had more photos. Things are different there now. The Strawberry Fields property is now a museum experience. If you look at my shot, there’s just the field and property there, now, you’ll see a modern MCM like museum, which is great, but also turns it into a touristy thing. When we went in 2004, we were the only people there. 

When we returned we had a website meeting at his offices, and Paul showed up. We joked around, and later that night we went to see him perform at MSG.

From being in his office, with just six of us, to being in MSG with 19,000 fans, in a matter of hours, was something I’ll never forget! 

Were so lucky to have worked with him, but even more blessed to have these memories to share with you.

Back in 1954, Brian McClure loved attending grade school in the small town of Cold Spring, New York.

But, despite his boyish good looks, perfectly pleated pants, and shiny penny loafers, Brian was truly a fucking dumbass. 

Friends said his “belt didn’t go through all the loops,” so he simply didn’t wear one in retaliation, never fully getting the joke. While his teachers said he had an intellect rivaled only by a tree stump, Brian took it as a compliment because he loved trees.

Then there was Clara, dressed in her her favorite Christmas colors. Clara was an A student who excelled at math, stayed after school for extra curricular activities, and was involved in the photography club. She was the envy of all the kids at Haldane Elementary. Yet in a single day, Brian failed two tests, got into three fights and blew up the science lab.

While Brian had shit luck, allergic reactions to education, and was dumber than a box pubic hair, he still walked through life in a state of bliss.

15 years later, Brian ended up being the mayor of Cold Spring. His sister’s passion for photography led her to pornography, and their mom Brenda, who was crazier than a fish with tits, drove off a cliff into the Hudson and barely survived.

You never know the degree your life can mimic a Fellini film, until you drive your yellow “Big Wheel” all the way down the road to Nutsville!

Betsy Walgrove was delighted at the seating arrangement on the Greyhound bus to Brown Town.

She always eyed who’d be sitting in front of her, but not because she was going to strike up a conversation. Oh no. It was much more sinister than that.

Betsy liked to tickle the anuses of anyone in front of her with her pointy shoes, especially if they were attractive. This was a footish few people possessed.

Betsy would start with a simple test-poke, light and tentative, just barely knocking on the backdoor. 

Sometimes they’d jump off their seat. And sometimes they’d look over their shoulder in an odd nervous nod of delight and approval—willing, but frightened.

With some, more adventurous travelers, Betsy would use the twister method, circling her toe like she was mixing cake. One man spun his head in such ecstasy that he nearly twisted his spine, ending with a whirling assgasm. 

While Betsy’s toe was cramped and stiff, she was pleased with her toe work.

The best was when she used two feet in what she called the turbo taint tickler. This she used for women traveling alone—for whom she knew would enjoy her fancy foot-in-ass frolic.

Over the years, traveling became an obsessive pastime for Betsy, until she was reported to the bus company by a man with severe hemorrhoids, whom she sent screaming out of the back emergency exit, nearly on fire. As much Preparation H as he slathered on his tight starfish, he was never prepared for Betsy’s toe in his achy achy ass.

Note to self: always look behind, below, and, be weary of pointy toe’d women on the Greyhound bus—Betsy’s been seen around with deadly Prada shoes lately!

For what some would call a bizarre life, Dick Masturson modeled in his spare time at the beckoning of his mother who thought “Dicky” had a certain pizzaz.

At his day job as a pornography historian at the MOMP, the Museum of Modern Porn, it was “bring your mom to work day,” and Dick’s mom finally got to see what her son REALLY did for a living. While not born with the proper endowment to be in the pornography business, per se, Dicky was the curator, and wrote about all the stars, documenting their every film and position.

For the museum’s display cases he wrote quick blurbs about porn star Rocky Balboner, known for having a large jabber with a serious left hook. Legends like Luke Thighwalker, known for his red saber and calling everyone “daddy.” He also dickumented the life of Sir Cumfrence, previously Dildo Gaggings, who had a thing for elven boys. All of it on display for all to enjoy. Mom did not like this.

Dicky’s day job at the MOMP ended abruptly in 1978, when he slipped on a dildo and went crashing into a couple enjoying the Boner Lisa. It was a massacre of houndstooth pants, tube socks, lube, and mustaches, resulting in thousands of dollars in damage, and a lawsuit by the couple.

So back to this catalog shoot—Charmless, feckless, dickless Dicky suggested the pretty model be in a subservient position for this Sears Fall 1976 catalog shoot, leading to a Sears boycott by a women’s empowerment group in 1977. 

Dicky was never rehired, accused by Sears of causing sales to “slump like his penis.” He did however trademark this dashing pose as the “breaking bad!” This was his only legacy.

Still mad at the world, Dicky never married, and lives with his mom, where she repurposed his corduroys into kitchen drapes. He now works at a post office in Peoria.

This is still the look he gives people when they ask if he’s Bryan Cranston.

A bizarre life indeed.

Back in 1965, on Friday nights, there was always something special cooking in the kitchen for Johnny and Kate.

With mom religiously watching Julia Child on TV, everything was cooked in French crocks, and the children always had a look of wonder on their faces—but mostly because they could never tell what the hell they were about to eat. 

“Hey sis? What in Annette Funicello is that?” Johnny asked. “I don’t know Johnny, yours could be meat, could be cake?” Johnny looked back at his sis with that one good tooth and smiled. “I hope it’s meatcake!” he replied emphatically!

Kate’s lamb stew with peas, potatoes and carrots, burned the roof of Kate’s tongue, and knocked the teeth right out of her mouth, but not before the second degree burns to her hands set in.

Mom had forgotten to tell the kids the crockpots were boiling lava hot, so a quick visit to the ER is how they spent their Friday night.

On a positive note, Mom’s meat cake won the annual Women’s Cooking League “Cook-Off” in Larchmont, again, three years in a row. While the ingredients are unknown, rumour has it, her minced beef and coffee cake streusel recipe was made by accident when Johnny stuck the bottom half of a cake recipe to the top half of a Minced Meat Pie recipe in mom’s cookbook.

Described by Mom’s enemies as a “beatsauce from a Kentucky jail,” —no one could quite put a finger on it, but heck, there was something truly special about that meatcake!

Troy knew just how to get Shamus in a good mood, and nothing perked him up like a fresh cup of Joe. By the third cup, Troy thought nothing of leaning on Shamus, teasing Shamus, and rubbing up against Shamus, who was known on campus to have a creamy jock full of nuts.

Shamus signaled that a break was in order, but Troy was at the ready for some serious coconut clapping, which seemed like a step too far for Shamus.

He denied being gay, and Troy suspected he wasn’t a true lispian, so he went back to studying to avoid getting Shamus mad.

But, was Shamus in the gay waiting room, eventually on his way to riding the rainbow trolley? This time, he was closer than ever!

It was a study session drawn from the anals of the gaycyclopedia dramatica—a love story of boy meets boy, boy drools on boy, other boy feigns disgust, they both shag for three hours and never talk again. The end.

Peggy loves her new lightweight Electrolux vacuum cleaner so much that she could lift it with one finger, that is, until that one day when she couldn’t.

Aside from holding a bread-winning job at the local accountants office as an executive, she is a clean-freak-neat-nick, who spends Sunday mornings just before church sucking up toys and various other things that seemed to make her canister a collection device more than a cleaning appliance.

When Peg went to empty the canister one day, it was heavier than usual. She noticed an orange ball of fur that was sticking out of the canister door. For a quick second, it APPEARED to move, until it DEFINITELY moved!
Peggy had somehow left the canister open after changing the bag, and Ginger, her prized and inquisitive feline, had managed to get inside of it, seeking to cover Peggy’s home in dust and green plastic army men.

Peg is now recovering from IITTKMCG (I-involuntarily-tried-to-kill-my-cat-guilt). 

Ginger is fine, with the exception of being partially deaf in one ear and occasionally coughing dust clouds.

Jules was thrilled when he and his sister Jackie received shiny Buster Brown shoes for Christmas!

Jules was a precocious child. Peas? No. Sports? No. Flannel? Heck no. Fine clothing, chandeliers, chartreuse, Jean Nate? Yes!

As a child, young Jules admired L’Oreal models, Avon Salesladies and TWA Stewardesses. He color-coordinated his clothing to match the living room chairs.
His bedroom curtains matched the comforter, and at any time, you could hear South Pacific being played on his phonograph.

At one time, Jules was so well coordinated that his mother and father could not find him for days—a perfect blend of human and color coordinates.

As he grew into his teens, Jules turned into a charming young gay man who wouldn’t be caught dead in Buster Browns, but his coming out story at 15 was one for the books—during a time of great volatility and hate.

In a risky move, Jules made his mom an interesting little greeting card by cutting out the busts of Liberace, Montgomery Clift, Tab Hunter, Elvis, from a magazine, and a school picture of himself. He pasted the four celebrities and his own face in a row across the middle of the card and folded it. The front of the card read: “Which one of these people is NOT GAY?” And, on the inside, the card read, “Answer: Elvis.” He left the card on the kitchen table and ran upstairs, disappearing into his bedroom. A perfectly acceptable invisibility cloak.

By the time they found Jules, he was 18 and on his way to San Francisco!

Their suckamental income as Avon girls did little to get them to Uptown status, but they looked fabulous shopping the racks nevertheless. They had a maximal propensity to consume and bus tickets back to Mamaroneck, to the all-too-realness of working class life.

Waiting at home, they had husbands and casserole nights. They forgot all their troubles and cares, they enjoyed their movie shows, and the neon lights of Sal’s Pizzeria.

They were downtown girls, and that’s just the way they liked it.

The party at the McMurray’s was a smashing success, even though the virus reared its ugly head again in the fall.

Everyone social distanced their asses off, wore masks, and Hal McMurray even tore off the side of the house to qualify as an “outdoor” gathering. They were desperate to see their friends!

Rectal temperatures and a virus “quick test” were taken before entering, and people brought their own tuna casseroles, while the music of Henry Mancini filled the air for the first party at the McMurry’s since March.

Even strangers asked if they could join, but the McMurrays had to reject them in order to keep the party under 20. People with no masks were driven to the dessert and left for dead.

There were what they called two different sets of people, “lifers,” (those who liked breathing), and “permanent vacationers,” (those who thought the virus was a hoax.)

Many felt muzzled and refused to wear a mask indoors. They’re dead now. But it was clear, killing off their family members, friends, and strangers really gave them a sense of “freedom and liberty.” They were true patriots!

As the lights dimmed on Juniper Hill, a good time was had by all.

Even thought everyone had post-party depression the next day, it was so very much better than death!

By 10pm, Brianne was faceshat. Shoes were flung out the window, marriage propositions to hobos were made while vomiting, and improper hand gestures were followed by out-of-tune singing, which eventually took it’s toll on Janet, and especially Max.

Max took the Henry Hudson up to Katonah, a.k.a. “the middle of fuckin’ nowhere,” leaving Brianne in a field with cows and goats, “helping” her sober up.

Janet and Max never took her out with them again, but later that year, Max hired Brianne at his dealership and Brianne got to rIde in the backseat for every test drive, minus the booze of course.

Today, Brianne is married to six homeless men, and still cannot hold a tune!

When Sandra booked a flight to London for she and her husband Paul, she was attracted by the notion of friendliness and kindness on a long trip. Little did she know, Leighann Whitford would be their stewardess.

A Monday Mystery.

Danny Montvale fell for it again. A handsome younger man, a yellow windbreaker, the big thumb. Danny was in for a surprise.

Danny had just finished Yale in 1962 when his dad gave him a new car as a gift for graduating Sum Cumma Loudly. He wasn’t flamboyant or over-the-top, but he did have a flair for picking up guys near his school, and a reputation for using his father’s money to lure in the less fortunate, destitute and troubled. It was when he picked up Derek Fischer that things made a turn for the worse.

Derek introduced himself with a sheepish smile, and the two drove around the area for a while getting to know one another and talking about where they would settle for their quick exchange. Would it be the college library, the bath house, Derek’s apartment, or Danny’s parents home just nearby in Santa Barbara?

The two would never arrive. While Danny went inside the gas station to pick up a pack of Luck Strikes, Derek hopped in the front seat and took off with his new car, leaving Danny stranded near Stearns Warf.

Derek’s usual game was to steal a car and flip it for cash. Derek wasn’t even a homosexual. He was an evil, scheming, low-life, who used his good looks and big thumbs to get he and his girlfriend the drugs they needed. The yellow coat was stolen from the valet at the country club down the road after Derek left the young kid for dead in a parking lot.

It was a sad tale of a Californian imposter. A tale brimming with lies and deceptions—a pattern that was hard for Derek to break. How long before he got caught? How long would it be until his victim would catch on to his game and turn the tables on him?
Would Derek go gay-for-pay when the word was out he was the car jacker?

Find out more by immersing yourself into The Gay Trap. A gripping new novel by Don Holliday.

Customer support at Norelco wasn’t always so reliable, but Janine Lebuthier had all the time to wait for a representative.

With the advent of hair drying technology hitting its stride in 1965, with variable temperature control, it wasn’t uncommon for women in America to call customer support to ask what settings were best for optimum curling.

For Janine, her trouble began when Sarah Perry, lead drierologist at Norelco, answered the phone, bored to tears and ready to unload.
She was eager to tell her fairy tale divorce story to Janine—a sort of “capptive audience,” if you will.

First, she started about the restraining order, and the start of her conscious uncoupling, all this while Janine’s hair tightened and tightened around each spool.
She continued about how her deadbeat husband led her to dollar store cookies, and bagged cereals on the bottom shelf at Shop-Rite. It was a horror.

Janine listened, but in her normal apathetic style, offered nothing but sighs and limpathy. It was when Sarah started crying that she realized she was mourning at the wrong corpse. Janine was done with this conversation and wasn’t getting the help she needed.

“Sorry m’aam, but I just called to ask how long to stay under the dryer when in the middle position!”

Sarah had her finger in the middle position properly erected and hung up in disgust.
She threw up her arms and asked, “where can a women have an honest-to-goodness bitching session around here!”

The office was vacant. All of Sarah’s phone support co-workers had quit in frustration with Sarah to work at the new insurance company. They now call homes asking about your car’s extended warranty. Sarah works as a divorce counselor at the state’s social services department. Janine never dares to call customer support anymore with new appliances—she just reads the manual!

As a devout atheist, little William Cooper(back right) distanced himself from his family as they went from home to home, trying to proselytute themselves in the name of God. 

While his siblings rejoiced in being the children of God, their parents Sarah and Joseph, were constantly busy sewing outfits for family photos on their ‘76 Christploitation Tour.  The fact that they dressed the same was a testament to the idea that “being unique was being a freak.”

But, William always made sure the world knew that he was not Mormonic like them, especially when they walked the neighborhood and posed for photos in stranger’s living rooms. 

At 18, William was somewhat of an oxy-mormon—a rebellious and pot smoking child who eventually came out of the closet, renounced his religion, cast sweater vests out of his wardrobe, and went from Mormon to More-men.

Good for you, Billy. What’s the use in being “God’s child” when you were the only one in the family to eat Fruit Loops for breakfast? He had a plan for you all along!

Louise vowed to do at least one thing every day that scared the shit out of her, so she called her mother-in-law.

It was a normal Monday morning. The promise of disappointment and dread filled the kitchen as Louise made breakfast for her family. But just before she started flipping the flapjacks, she thought she’d fuck her day right up and call Clara, her six headed smother-in-law.

To say they both had a rocky relationship was an understatement, but Louise literally blew bubbles out her ass to make Clara believe she liked her.

This was next-level ass-kissing, known as crackspackling, meant to keep her husband Hal happy and to create the illusion of peace in the family.

Louise’s best “get off the phone quick trick” was making believe Hal wanted to say hi.
“Haaaallll!,” she yelled across the kitchen, “didn’t you want to ask your mom something?

Hal would whisper, “I will kill you when she hangs up,” so his mom couldn’t hear.

After each dreaded Monday call, the sun would come out, birds would sing on the kitchen windowsill, and she knew the week couldn’t possibly get any worse.

Be gone, Monday.
You have no power here!

Carly Miller’s newest gift to herself was a marvelous invention that had all the women on 
Devereaux Avenue talking about it, but for very different reasons.

One afternoon, in early autumn, Carly was suffering from yet another bout of compulsive housewife disorder. Pumpkin Pies, Pound Cakes, and Banana Loafs were on her list of baking priorities for the season. Being the supermanagizer she was, multi-tasking was her strong suit. 

However, with her job at the Provident Bank, and other duties at the Ladies Auxiliary, Carly had to perform miracles to get things done at home.

As she filled the bowl with Betty Crocker, she mistakenly turned around while her new TurboBlow X666 did its duty to suck in the entire cake mix through the intake straddled on her waist. 

Her hair balloon quickly filled up with the powdery cake mix, and combined with her hair and setting lotion—then it happened. Upon removing the hair bag, her hair, the lotion and cake mix created a chocolaty Upside Down Cake on her head. 

Children, aphids and other animals quickly nuzzled up to Carly’s head as she created a new hair moisturizing regimen adopted years later by Vidal Sassoon in the 70s.

When she was hungry at church service later, she just ran her fingers through her hair for a quick snack. 

The TurboBlow X666. 
The Devil’s Foodcake is in the details.

Loraine was stuck in carmageddon and never wanted to go to another football game again. She always preferred romance over sports.

“Oh, that’s Caroline. Remember her?,” she said disapprovingly.

As Gwen and Hal looked through their photo album, many memories came flooding back like a backed up toilet at the IHOP.

Like that time they went to the Poconos in the 70s and stayed at Mt. Airy Lodge and and got robbed. That time Hal briefly worked at the Burger King to make ends meet, and in 1979 when the couple went on vacation to Candlewood Lake and Hal fell down a flight of stairs at the feet of Paul Lynde at the Riverside Banquette. Memories.

So many good times to laugh about, but Caroline, the young lady who lived across the street was a constant source of entertainment for Gwen, who spent days and days eating Social Tea biscuits and sipping Lipton tea by the window while watching Caroline’s every move.

One day, Caroline had at least three boys from College Boy Painters, visit to paint her house from yellow, to blue and then finally pink. Caroline couldn’t make up her mind, and had handsome painters there every other week.

The following week, Gwen nearly choked on a biscuit when she witnessed eight young boys walk in the side door, and not one of them walked out with a single paint spot on their pristine white overalls.

As Gwen recalls the special people in her life, she was reminded that something got a good white paint job that day, and it wasn’t the house. From that day forward, Caroline was never liked.

Were the painters really that clean?
Did they take their turn with Caroline.

Hal, a gentle and pensive man, sat there and wondered about their own kitchen, and pondered if it too was painted repeatedly during this period.

He looked at Gwen, then at the walls, and thought, “thank goodness they’re wallpapered!”

Serious note: For those without family or friends this holiday season and those battling depression, there are always people and communities here on Instagram for support. 

Even after the holidays, people can suffer from depression because the “party’s over.” Just know that surrounding yourself with positivity and good people can help. Laughter can help as well, but for those who suffer from clinical depression, it’s not that simple, and that advice puts a temporary bandage on a much larger wound. I ask that if this is the case, please seek out help, especially if you feel suicidal or have thoughts of hurting yourself. If you need a resource to call, consider the mental health hotline dot org. 

Soldier suicides are especially high in this country this time of year. Loneliness, drug addiction, PTSD, feelings of inadequacy, depression and poor financial situations lead to a feelings of helplessness.

If you’re a U.S. Vet, please check out the wide array of avenues to help you through your dark hours. 

Laughter is good too, but professional support will hopefully get you a path to healing. 

Love to you all, Bobby. ❤️

In early January, 1959, Robert and Brigitte’s dinner seemed likely to be sabotaged by New England’s inclement weather.

The newspapers reported a “blizzard” was heading to the East Coast, and Litchfield would not be spared. Even the Farmer’s Almanac made an accurate prediction. But, Brigitte’s hopes were truly dashed when seven inches turned to a foot in just two hours.

Carolyn and Brett, Suzanne and Lee, Marcus and Dave were all supposed arrive at 6pm. As Robert paced, Brigitte put the finishing touches on the massive festive spread. Dave Brubeck’s “Time Out” played softly on the Magnovox console, but Robert had to keep moving the needle back to the beginning for the most perfect entrance song. The smell of pine permeated the already fragrant air, yet no one was coming.

At 7pm sharp, the phone rang, Brigitte’s heart beat out of her chest, as if the drummer boy himself was doing paradiddles with her heart. Robert raced to the phone, preparing himself for the worst.

“Bobby, it’s Lee,” a man on the other end said, breathless.

“If it’s bad news, I don’t wanna hear it Lee,” Robert quipped.

“Well.....” Lee dragged on, “Carolyn and Brett’s car wouldn’t start, Marcus and Dave are with us. We all piled in the my car and we’re leaving in five minutes. We’re gonna make it. They cleared North Street, but I have bad news. We’re all staying over tonight.”

“Of course you are! Of course!,” Robert said excitedly, Brigitte’s already set up the guest rooms!”

“We’ll be there within the hour!”

It would be the most magical night Brigitte and Robert would ever have in their new home on Minerva Lane—a testament to the adventurous spirit of New Englanders.

As his hands got fancy on the ivory, Jimmy moved as far way from that finger as he could. Thank Jesus, Delores came in when she did to lure Harvey away into the kitchen with prunes.

Mary hated short guys. Some called her a “Height Supremacist,” but she had her reasons.

Make no mistake about it, Mary Wellworth was a lover of long, leggy guys with slouch socks and hi tops.

But it was really the knee pads that got her all bubbly inside. She knew a man with padded knees was ready to do the necessary work to keep her satisfied.

After attending 14 basketball games in a row at her high school, Mary made an impression on Bobby Moreland, but was he a Shooting Guard or a Small Forward?
Nope, none of those. Bobby was a Swingman and heavily involved with Tommy Morrison who was the team’s Power Forward.

Mary was shit out of luck and hanging out at the snack bar, sipping 7up, eating 6 hot dogs and her feelings of inadequacy.

She soon went back to her job at McDowell’s as a plaid clad server. That night she saw Bobby and Tommy there who came to have a quick after-game dinner.

She knew Bobby and Tommy needed to quench their dry throats with refreshing 7up.

“Wait a minute, is this 7up or Mellow Yellow?” Bobby asked?

“Why, yes!” Mary said emphatically. It’s Mellow Yellow”

She was done with Bobby and tall guys, and that Tommy too.

Mary felt relieved. Like, really relieved!
